<?php

namespace App\Support;

use Illuminate\Support\Str;

class BlogArticleDefinitions
{
    public static function all(): array
    {
        return [
            self::article('How to Calculate GST in India (With Examples)', 'how-to-calculate-gst-in-india', 'How to Calculate GST in India with Examples - Toolexa', 'Learn how GST is calculated in India with inclusive and exclusive GST examples, formulas, tax slabs and practical invoice scenarios.', 'Finance', 'A practical GST guide for Indian invoices, inclusive prices and business calculations.', ['gst-calculator', 'percentage-calculator'], [
                ['Introduction to GST calculation', ['GST is an indirect tax added to the supply of many goods and services in India. In everyday use, the important question is simple: are you adding tax to a base amount, or extracting tax from a final price that already includes GST?', 'For shoppers, GST explains why the invoice total can be higher than the listed taxable value. For business owners, it affects quotes, invoices, revenue records, input tax credit checks and the way totals are presented to customers.']],
                ['Step-by-step guide', ['First identify the GST rate. Next decide whether the amount is GST exclusive or GST inclusive. For an exclusive amount, multiply the base value by the rate and add the result. For an inclusive amount, divide the final price by one plus the tax rate.', 'Use the GST Calculator when you need a fast answer, then use the Percentage Calculator when you want to explain the percentage math behind the result to a teammate, customer or student.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['If a product costs Rs. 2,500 before tax and GST is 12 percent, GST is Rs. 300 and the final price is Rs. 2,800. If a bill is Rs. 1,180 including 18 percent GST, the taxable value is Rs. 1,000 and GST is Rs. 180.', 'Inclusive calculations are common when an invoice, restaurant bill or marketplace receipt shows only the final amount. Exclusive calculations are common when preparing a quote before tax is added.']],
                ['Tips for accurate invoices', ['Always mention whether prices are inclusive or exclusive. Keep taxable value, GST amount and final amount in separate columns. For intra-state invoices, check CGST and SGST split; for inter-state invoices, check IGST treatment.', 'Rounding can create tiny differences, so use a consistent method across invoices. For compliance-sensitive work, confirm GST rates from official sources or a qualified professional.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['The biggest mistake is applying GST twice to an amount that already includes tax. Another common mistake is using 18 percent by habit when the product or service belongs to a different slab.', 'People also confuse discount and tax order. If a discount applies before GST, calculate tax after reducing the taxable value, not on the original price.']],
                ['When GST tools save time', ['A calculator is helpful when you need quick invoice checks, quote preparation, bill splitting or tax extraction from inclusive receipts. It reduces arithmetic errors and keeps the formula consistent.', 'For repeated work, create a spreadsheet or billing system. For one-off checks, Toolexa tools are faster because you can enter the amount, choose the rate and copy the result.']],
            ], [
                ['How do I calculate 18 percent GST?', 'Multiply the taxable value by 18 and divide by 100. Add the result to the taxable value for the final price.'],
                ['How do I remove GST from an inclusive price?', 'Divide the inclusive price by 1.18 for 18 percent GST, then subtract that base value from the final price.'],
                ['Is GST calculated on MRP?', 'MRP is usually tax inclusive, so GST is already included and must be extracted for accounting.'],
                ['What is the difference between CGST, SGST and IGST?', 'CGST and SGST are generally used for intra-state supply, while IGST is used for inter-state supply.'],
                ['Can I use an online GST calculator for invoices?', 'Yes, for quick estimates and checks. Verify official rates and records for filing or compliance.'],
            ]),
            self::article('EMI Calculator Explained: Calculate Loans Easily', 'emi-calculator-explained-calculate-loans-easily', 'EMI Calculator Explained - Calculate Loans Easily', 'Understand how EMI is calculated for home, car, personal and education loans with formula, examples and practical repayment tips.', 'Finance', 'Understand EMI formulas, interest impact and repayment planning before choosing a loan.', ['emi-calculator', 'loan-calculator', 'home-loan-emi-calculator', 'personal-loan-emi-calculator'], [
                ['Introduction to EMI', ['EMI means Equated Monthly Instalment. It is the fixed monthly payment used to repay many loans, including home loans, car loans, personal loans and education loans.', 'Each EMI contains interest and principal. In the early months, interest is usually a larger share. Later, more of the payment reduces the outstanding principal.']],
                ['Step-by-step guide', ['Start with loan amount, annual interest rate and tenure. Convert the annual rate into a monthly rate, convert tenure into months, and apply the EMI formula. The formula works, but manual calculation is easy to mistype.', 'A loan calculator removes formula friction. Enter the amount, rate and term, then compare different tenures before you apply.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['A Rs. 5,00,000 personal loan at 11 percent for five years will have a higher EMI than the same loan for seven years, but the longer loan usually costs more total interest.', 'For a home loan, a small rate difference can matter because the loan amount and tenure are large. Testing 8.5 percent versus 9 percent can show a meaningful repayment gap.']],
                ['Tips for choosing EMI', ['Do not choose a loan only because the EMI looks low. Check total interest, processing fees, prepayment rules, insurance costs and whether the rate is fixed or floating.', 'A comfortable EMI leaves room for rent, groceries, emergency savings, school fees and unexpected repairs. Borrowing should fit life, not squeeze it.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['The common mistake is extending tenure too much just to lower monthly EMI. It can make the loan look affordable while quietly increasing total interest.', 'Another mistake is ignoring existing EMIs. Lenders and households both care about total monthly debt load, not only the new loan.']],
                ['When to recalculate EMI', ['Recalculate EMI when interest rates change, you make a prepayment, you change tenure, or you compare a new loan offer. The same calculator can help before and after approval.', 'For category-specific planning, use Home Loan EMI, Personal Loan EMI or Education Loan EMI calculators because the assumptions and decisions can differ.']],
            ], [
                ['What is EMI?', 'EMI is the fixed monthly payment used to repay a loan over a selected tenure.'],
                ['Does lower EMI mean cheaper loan?', 'Not always. Lower EMI from longer tenure can increase total interest.'],
                ['Can EMI change after approval?', 'Yes, floating-rate loans, prepayments or restructuring can change EMI or tenure.'],
                ['Which is better, shorter tenure or lower EMI?', 'Shorter tenure saves interest if you can afford the higher payment comfortably.'],
                ['Can I calculate EMI manually?', 'Yes, but calculators are faster and reduce formula mistakes.'],
            ]),
            self::article('Simple vs Compound Interest: What\'s the Difference?', 'simple-vs-compound-interest-difference', 'Simple vs Compound Interest - Key Difference with Examples', 'Compare simple interest and compound interest with formulas, examples and practical saving and borrowing scenarios.', 'Finance', 'Learn how simple and compound interest behave differently over time.', ['simple-interest-calculator', 'compound-interest-calculator', 'percentage-calculator'], [
                ['Introduction', ['Simple interest calculates interest only on the original principal. Compound interest calculates interest on principal plus previously earned interest.', 'The difference may look small at first, but time changes everything. Over longer periods, compounding can create a much larger final value or a much larger debt.']],
                ['Step-by-step comparison', ['For simple interest, multiply principal by rate and time. For compound interest, add interest back to the balance each period and calculate the next period from the larger balance.', 'Use the Simple Interest Calculator to create a baseline, then compare the same principal, rate and time in the Compound Interest Calculator.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['If Rs. 1,00,000 earns 8 percent simple interest for five years, interest is Rs. 40,000. With annual compounding, the final amount is higher because each year starts with a larger balance.', 'For loans, compounding can work against you when unpaid interest is added to the balance. Credit card debt is a familiar example.']],
                ['Tips for understanding growth', ['Always check compounding frequency. Annual, quarterly and monthly compounding can produce different results even when the headline rate is the same.', 'For investments, focus on realistic returns and long time horizons. For debt, focus on early repayment and avoiding unpaid interest.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['A common mistake is comparing a simple annual rate with a compounded return as if they are identical. The calculation method changes the outcome.', 'Another mistake is ignoring time. Compounding rewards patience, but it also punishes long-running expensive debt.']],
                ['Where each method appears', ['Simple interest is often used for straightforward examples and some short-term calculations. Compound interest appears in savings growth, investments, recurring returns and many debt products.', 'Knowing which method is being used helps you read offers, compare plans and avoid being impressed by numbers that are not comparable.']],
            ], [
                ['Which is better, simple or compound interest?', 'Compound interest is usually better for savers and investors, while simple interest is easier and may cost less for borrowers.'],
                ['Why does compounding grow faster?', 'Because interest is added to the balance and future interest is calculated on that larger amount.'],
                ['Does compounding frequency matter?', 'Yes. More frequent compounding usually increases the final amount for the same nominal rate.'],
                ['Can compound interest apply to debt?', 'Yes, it can increase debt when unpaid interest gets added to the balance.'],
                ['Which calculator should I use?', 'Use simple interest for basic interest-only examples and compound interest for reinvested growth or compounding periods.'],
            ]),
            self::article('SIP vs FD vs RD vs PPF: Which Investment is Better?', 'sip-vs-fd-vs-rd-vs-ppf', 'SIP vs FD vs RD vs PPF - Which Investment is Better?', 'Compare SIP, fixed deposit, recurring deposit and PPF by risk, return, liquidity, tax treatment and goal suitability.', 'Finance', 'Compare four popular saving and investment choices for Indian households.', ['sip-calculator', 'fd-calculator', 'rd-calculator', 'ppf-calculator', 'cagr-calculator'], [
                ['Introduction', ['SIP, FD, RD and PPF are popular because they support different saving habits. SIP is market-linked investing, FD is lump-sum deposit, RD is monthly deposit and PPF is long-term tax-friendly saving.', 'The better choice depends on goal, risk comfort, time horizon and whether you need predictable returns or growth potential.']],
                ['Step-by-step comparison', ['Start by defining the goal: emergency fund, school fees, house down payment, retirement or wealth creation. Then check time horizon, liquidity need, risk tolerance and tax impact.', 'Use calculators to test amounts instead of relying on labels. A safe product may be wrong for long-term growth, while a growth product may be wrong for short-term certainty.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['For a three-month emergency fund, FD may be more suitable than equity SIP. For monthly discipline over two years, RD can be simple. For fifteen-year disciplined saving, PPF can be attractive.', 'For a ten-year wealth goal, SIP may offer higher growth potential, but the value can fluctuate. The SIP Calculator helps model regular contributions with realistic expected returns.']],
                ['Tips for choosing', ['Do not force one product to solve every goal. Many households use FD for safety, RD for short-term discipline, PPF for long-term conservative saving and SIP for growth.', 'Review liquidity. Money needed soon should not be exposed to market swings or locked into long commitments.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['A common mistake is comparing guaranteed FD returns with expected SIP returns as if both have the same risk. They do not.', 'Another mistake is ignoring lock-in. PPF is powerful for long-term saving, but it is not designed for quick access.']],
                ['How calculators help', ['Use FD Calculator for lump-sum deposits, RD Calculator for monthly deposits, PPF Calculator for long-term contributions and SIP Calculator for market-linked monthly investing.', 'CAGR Calculator helps compare completed investments by converting total growth into an annualized rate.']],
            ], [
                ['Is SIP better than FD?', 'SIP can offer higher long-term growth potential, but FD is more predictable. Better depends on risk and time horizon.'],
                ['Is PPF safer than SIP?', 'PPF is generally more conservative, while SIP is market-linked and can fluctuate.'],
                ['Which is best for monthly saving?', 'RD is predictable and SIP is growth-oriented. Choose based on goal duration and risk comfort.'],
                ['Can I invest in more than one option?', 'Yes, using a mix often works better than choosing only one.'],
                ['Should I decide only by return?', 'No. Consider risk, liquidity, tax rules, lock-in and goal timing.'],
            ]),
            self::article('How Inflation Affects Your Savings', 'how-inflation-affects-your-savings', 'How Inflation Affects Your Savings - Simple Guide', 'Understand how inflation reduces purchasing power, affects savings returns and changes long-term financial planning.', 'Finance', 'Learn why rising prices matter when you save, invest and plan future goals.', ['inflation-calculator', 'compound-interest-calculator', 'sip-calculator', 'fd-calculator'], [
                ['Introduction', ['Inflation means prices rise over time. Even when your bank balance stays the same, the amount it can buy may shrink.', 'This is why financial planning is not only about saving money. It is also about preserving purchasing power and choosing returns that can keep pace with rising costs.']],
                ['Step-by-step guide', ['Start with today\'s cost of a goal. Estimate an inflation rate. Calculate what the same goal may cost after five, ten or twenty years. Then compare that future cost with your saving plan.', 'The Inflation Calculator helps translate today\'s price into a future amount, making long-term goals feel more concrete.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['If education costs Rs. 5,00,000 today and inflation averages 6 percent, the future cost after ten years can be much higher. A flat savings target may fall short.', 'For household budgets, inflation shows up in groceries, rent, transport, school fees and healthcare. Small monthly increases can become large annual differences.']],
                ['Tips to protect savings', ['Keep emergency money accessible, but do not keep every long-term rupee idle. For long goals, consider products with growth potential suited to your risk profile.', 'Review goals annually. If inflation or lifestyle costs rise faster than expected, increase contributions early rather than waiting until the deadline.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['A common mistake is celebrating nominal returns without checking real returns. If your deposit earns 5 percent and inflation is 6 percent, purchasing power may still fall.', 'Another mistake is using the same inflation rate for every goal. Healthcare and education can rise differently from general household expenses.']],
                ['Inflation and calculators', ['Use the Inflation Calculator to estimate future costs, SIP Calculator for regular investing scenarios and Compound Interest Calculator to understand growth over time.', 'These tools do not predict the future perfectly, but they help you plan with assumptions instead of guesses.']],
            ], [
                ['What is inflation?', 'Inflation is the rise in prices over time, which reduces the purchasing power of money.'],
                ['How does inflation affect savings?', 'It can make saved money buy less in the future if returns do not keep up.'],
                ['What is real return?', 'Real return is investment return after adjusting for inflation.'],
                ['Can inflation be predicted exactly?', 'No, but estimates help with long-term planning.'],
                ['Which tool helps estimate future costs?', 'The Inflation Calculator helps estimate how today\'s cost may change over time.'],
            ]),
            self::article('Complete Guide to Home Loan EMI Calculation', 'complete-guide-to-home-loan-emi-calculation', 'Complete Guide to Home Loan EMI Calculation', 'Learn how home loan EMI is calculated, how rate and tenure affect repayments and how to compare home loan scenarios.', 'Finance', 'A practical guide for understanding home loan EMI before choosing a lender.', ['home-loan-emi-calculator', 'mortgage-calculator', 'emi-calculator', 'loan-calculator'], [
                ['Introduction', ['A home loan is often the largest loan a household takes. EMI looks simple on the surface, but rate, tenure, down payment and prepayment choices can change total cost dramatically.', 'Understanding home loan EMI helps you compare offers, plan monthly cash flow and avoid choosing a tenure only because the first number looks comfortable.']],
                ['Step-by-step guide', ['Enter the loan amount after down payment, the annual interest rate and the loan term in years. The calculator converts rate and tenure into monthly values and estimates EMI.', 'Next, test alternate scenarios. Change only one input at a time: rate, tenure or loan amount. This shows which factor affects your payment most.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['A Rs. 40 lakh loan for 20 years will have a lower EMI than the same loan for 15 years, but the 20-year loan usually costs more interest.', 'Even a 0.25 percent rate difference can matter over long tenures. Compare offers using the same loan amount and tenure before deciding.']],
                ['Tips for home buyers', ['Keep EMI comfortable enough to handle maintenance, insurance, society charges, taxes and emergencies. Home ownership has costs beyond the loan.', 'Ask lenders about processing fees, prepayment charges, rate reset rules, insurance bundling and documentation before judging only by EMI.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['A common mistake is calculating EMI on property price instead of actual loan amount after down payment. Another is ignoring floating-rate risk.', 'Some buyers also forget that a lower EMI from a longer tenure may increase total interest. Always compare total repayment.']],
                ['Amortization basics', ['In early years, more EMI goes toward interest. Over time, principal repayment increases. This is why prepayments made early can reduce interest more strongly.', 'Use the Home Loan EMI Calculator and Mortgage Calculator to review monthly payment, total interest and amortization summary.']],
            ], [
                ['What inputs are needed for home loan EMI?', 'Loan amount, annual interest rate and loan tenure are the key inputs.'],
                ['Does EMI include taxes and insurance?', 'Usually EMI calculators focus on principal and interest, not property taxes or insurance.'],
                ['Does longer tenure reduce EMI?', 'Yes, but it usually increases total interest paid.'],
                ['Can prepayment reduce interest?', 'Yes, especially when made early, subject to lender rules.'],
                ['Which Toolexa tool should I use?', 'Use Home Loan EMI Calculator or Mortgage Calculator for home-loan scenarios.'],
            ]),
            self::article('How to Choose the Right Personal Loan', 'how-to-choose-the-right-personal-loan', 'How to Choose the Right Personal Loan', 'Learn how to compare personal loan interest rates, tenure, EMI, fees, eligibility and repayment comfort before borrowing.', 'Finance', 'A borrower-friendly checklist for comparing personal loan offers.', ['personal-loan-emi-calculator', 'loan-calculator', 'emi-calculator', 'percentage-calculator'], [
                ['Introduction', ['Personal loans are useful for urgent expenses, planned purchases or debt consolidation, but they are usually unsecured and can carry higher interest rates than secured loans.', 'Choosing the right loan means looking beyond approval speed. EMI, fees, tenure, repayment flexibility and total cost all matter.']],
                ['Step-by-step guide', ['Start by defining the amount you truly need. Compare interest rates from multiple lenders, then calculate EMI for each offer using the same tenure.', 'After EMI, check processing fees, prepayment rules, late-payment charges and whether the interest rate is fixed or variable.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['A loan with a slightly lower rate but high processing fee may not be cheaper for a short tenure. A longer tenure can reduce EMI but increase total interest.', 'If you borrow Rs. 2,00,000 for three years, compare the monthly EMI and total repayment before deciding whether the offer fits your income.']],
                ['Tips for safer borrowing', ['Keep EMI within a comfortable share of monthly income. Maintain an emergency buffer so one unexpected expense does not cause missed payments.', 'Borrow for clear needs, not because approval is available. Pre-approved offers can still be expensive if the loan is unnecessary.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['A common mistake is comparing only EMI and ignoring total repayment. Another is taking the maximum approved amount instead of the required amount.', 'Borrowers also overlook late fees and prepayment conditions, which can matter if income changes or you want to close the loan early.']],
                ['Using calculators wisely', ['Use the Personal Loan EMI Calculator for a focused estimate, Loan Calculator for broader repayment planning and Percentage Calculator to understand fees as a share of loan amount.', 'Run at least three cases: ideal tenure, shorter tenure and stress-case EMI. This gives a clearer borrowing decision.']],
            ], [
                ['What should I compare in a personal loan?', 'Compare rate, EMI, total repayment, fees, tenure and prepayment rules.'],
                ['Is the lowest EMI always best?', 'No. A low EMI from long tenure can increase total interest.'],
                ['Should I borrow the maximum approved amount?', 'Usually no. Borrow only what you need and can repay comfortably.'],
                ['Can I prepay a personal loan?', 'Often yes, but charges and rules vary by lender.'],
                ['Which calculator helps?', 'Use the Personal Loan EMI Calculator to estimate monthly repayment.'],
            ]),
            self::article('Best Free Online PDF Tools You Should Use', 'best-free-online-pdf-tools-you-should-use', 'Best Free Online PDF Tools You Should Use', 'Explore useful free PDF tools for page counting, metadata viewing, password checking, image conversion and PDF merging.', 'PDF Tools', 'A practical guide to everyday PDF tasks you can handle in the browser.', ['image-to-pdf-converter', 'pdf-page-counter', 'pdf-metadata-viewer', 'pdf-password-checker', 'pdf-merger'], [
                ['Introduction', ['PDF files are everywhere: invoices, resumes, labels, reports, forms and certificates. The challenge is that small PDF tasks often feel heavier than they should.', 'Free online PDF tools help with quick checks and simple conversions without opening full desktop software for every small job.']],
                ['Step-by-step guide', ['Identify the task first. Do you need to count pages, inspect metadata, check password protection, merge PDFs or convert images into a PDF?', 'Choose the matching Toolexa PDF tool, upload or select the file, review the result and download only when the output looks correct.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['Before submitting a document, use PDF Page Counter to confirm page count. Before sharing a file externally, use PDF Metadata Viewer to check visible document details.', 'If you scan images for a form, Image to PDF Converter can bundle them into a PDF. If a PDF will not open, PDF Password Checker can report whether it appears protected.']],
                ['Tips for PDF workflows', ['Name files clearly before merging. Keep originals until you confirm the final PDF. Check page order and file size before uploading to a portal.', 'For sensitive files, prefer tools that process locally where available and avoid uploading confidential documents to unknown services.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['A common mistake is merging files in the wrong order and noticing only after submission. Another is ignoring metadata that may reveal old titles or author names.', 'People also forget file-size limits. Compress images before converting to PDF if the final document becomes too large.']],
                ['Choosing the right tool', ['Use one focused PDF tool at a time. A page counter is not a merger, and a password checker is not a password remover.', 'Focused tools are easier to trust because the input, output and purpose are clear.']],
            ], [
                ['Are Toolexa PDF tools free?', 'Yes, the listed PDF tools are designed for free browser-based use.'],
                ['Can I merge PDF files?', 'Yes, use the PDF Merger tool.'],
                ['Can I check PDF page count?', 'Yes, PDF Page Counter reports the number of pages.'],
                ['Does PDF Password Checker remove passwords?', 'No, it only reports whether a PDF appears protected or readable.'],
                ['Can images be converted to PDF?', 'Yes, use Image to PDF Converter.'],
            ]),
            self::article('Image Compression Without Losing Quality', 'image-compression-without-losing-quality', 'Image Compression Without Losing Quality', 'Learn practical image compression tips for JPEG, PNG and WebP files, including resizing, quality settings and format choices.', 'Image Tools', 'Make images lighter for websites, forms and sharing while keeping them clear.', ['image-compressor', 'image-resizer', 'image-cropper', 'png-to-jpg-converter', 'jpg-to-png-converter'], [
                ['Introduction', ['Image compression reduces file size so pages load faster, uploads finish sooner and storage is easier to manage. Good compression keeps visible quality acceptable.', 'The goal is not to make every image tiny at any cost. The goal is to find the smallest file that still looks good for its purpose.']],
                ['Step-by-step guide', ['Start by cropping unnecessary edges. Resize the image to the dimensions you actually need. Then compress with a moderate quality setting and compare the preview.', 'If the result looks rough, increase quality or reduce resizing. If it still looks excellent, try a little more compression.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['A 4000-pixel photo used in a 900-pixel blog layout should be resized before compression. A logo with transparency may need PNG or WebP instead of JPG.', 'For product photos, inspect edges, labels and faces. Compression problems often appear first around text, gradients and sharp details.']],
                ['Tips for quality', ['Use JPG or WebP for photos, PNG for transparency and screenshots with sharp text. Avoid saving the same JPG repeatedly at low quality.', 'Keep a copy of the original image. Once detail is removed by lossy compression, it cannot be perfectly restored.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['A common mistake is compressing huge images without resizing. Another is using PNG for large photos where JPG or WebP would be much lighter.', 'Some users push quality too low and only check thumbnails. Always inspect the image at the size people will actually see it.']],
                ['Using Toolexa image tools', ['Use Image Resizer first when dimensions are too large, Image Compressor for file size reduction and Image Cropper when the frame includes unnecessary space.', 'Format converters help when a platform requires JPG or PNG specifically.']],
            ], [
                ['Can compression reduce quality?', 'Yes, lossy compression can reduce quality, but careful settings keep changes hard to notice.'],
                ['Should I resize before compressing?', 'Usually yes when original dimensions are larger than needed.'],
                ['Which format is best for photos?', 'JPG or WebP is usually better for photos than PNG.'],
                ['Is PNG always better quality?', 'PNG is lossless, but it can create much larger files.'],
                ['Can I compress images on mobile?', 'Yes, Toolexa image tools are responsive in modern mobile browsers.'],
            ]),
            self::article('QR Codes Explained: Uses, Benefits & Best Practices', 'qr-codes-explained-uses-benefits-best-practices', 'QR Codes Explained - Uses, Benefits and Best Practices', 'Understand QR codes, common uses, benefits, safety tips and best practices for creating scannable QR codes.', 'Utility', 'Learn how QR codes work and how to use them clearly and safely.', ['qr-generator', 'url-encoder-decoder', 'url-slug-generator'], [
                ['Introduction', ['A QR code is a scannable pattern that stores information such as a URL, text, contact detail or payment link. People scan it with a phone camera instead of typing.', 'QR codes are popular because they connect physical places to digital actions: menus, posters, packaging, classrooms, invoices and events.']],
                ['Step-by-step guide', ['Decide what the QR code should open. Keep the destination simple and mobile-friendly. Generate the code, test it on multiple phones, then place it where scanning is easy.', 'Use the QR Code Generator for quick creation and URL tools when the destination link needs cleanup before encoding.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['A restaurant can link to a menu, a teacher can share class resources, and a shop can place a product guide on packaging.', 'For events, QR codes can open registration forms, location maps or feedback pages. The best examples save typing and reduce confusion.']],
                ['Tips for better QR codes', ['Use enough contrast, leave quiet space around the code and print it large enough for the scanning distance. Shorter URLs often create simpler codes.', 'Always test the final printed or displayed version, not only the preview on your screen.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['A common mistake is linking to a page that is not mobile-friendly. Another is placing the code on a curved, reflective or low-contrast surface.', 'Do not change the destination without retesting. If the link breaks, the printed QR code becomes useless.']],
                ['Security and trust', ['Users should be cautious with unknown QR codes because they can hide suspicious links. Brands should show context near the code so people know what to expect.', 'Use clear labels like "Scan for menu" or "Scan to download invoice" instead of leaving the code unexplained.']],
            ], [
                ['What can a QR code store?', 'It can store URLs, plain text, contact details and other supported data types.'],
                ['Do QR codes expire?', 'Static QR codes do not expire by themselves, but the destination link can stop working.'],
                ['What makes a QR code easy to scan?', 'Good contrast, enough size and quiet space around the code improve scanning.'],
                ['Can QR codes be unsafe?', 'Unknown QR codes can lead to suspicious links, so scan carefully.'],
                ['Which Toolexa tool creates QR codes?', 'Use the QR Code Generator.'],
            ]),
            self::article('Password Security Guide: Create Strong Passwords', 'password-security-guide-create-strong-passwords', 'Password Security Guide - Create Strong Passwords', 'Learn how to create strong passwords, check password strength, avoid reuse and improve account security with practical habits.', 'Security', 'Simple password habits that make online accounts harder to compromise.', ['password-generator', 'password-strength-checker', 'random-string-generator'], [
                ['Introduction', ['Passwords protect email, banking, cloud storage, work tools and social accounts. A weak or reused password can expose far more than one website.', 'Good password security is mostly about length, uniqueness, randomness and recovery habits. You do not need drama; you need consistency.']],
                ['Step-by-step guide', ['Create a unique password for every important account. Use long random passwords or passphrases, save them in a trusted password manager and enable two-factor authentication.', 'Use Password Generator for new passwords and Password Strength Checker to understand why a password looks weak, medium or strong.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['A short password with symbols can still be weaker than a long random phrase. A reused strong password becomes dangerous if one website leaks it.', 'For work accounts, email and banking, prioritize unique generated passwords and MFA. These accounts often unlock other services.']],
                ['Tips for safer accounts', ['Avoid birthdays, names, phone numbers, keyboard patterns and common substitutions. Keep recovery email and phone number updated.', 'Change passwords after a breach, suspicious login or accidental sharing. Routine forced changes are less useful than unique passwords and MFA.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['The biggest mistake is password reuse. Attackers often try leaked credentials across many sites.', 'Another mistake is storing passwords in plain notes, screenshots or chat messages. Use a password manager instead.']],
                ['Checking strength responsibly', ['A strength checker is educational. It can show length, character variety and common weaknesses, but it cannot guarantee total security.', 'Do not paste real sensitive passwords into unknown websites. Toolexa strength checking runs locally in the browser.']],
            ], [
                ['How long should a password be?', 'Use at least 14 characters for important accounts when possible.'],
                ['Are symbols required?', 'Symbols help, but length, randomness and uniqueness matter more.'],
                ['Is a password generator safe?', 'A generator is useful when you store the result securely and do not reuse it.'],
                ['Should I use the same password twice?', 'No, every important account should have a unique password.'],
                ['What is the best extra protection?', 'Enable two-factor authentication for important accounts.'],
            ]),
            self::article('JSON Formatter & Validator Explained for Beginners', 'json-formatter-validator-explained-beginners', 'JSON Formatter and Validator Explained for Beginners', 'Learn what JSON formatting and validation mean, how to read JSON errors and how developers use JSON tools.', 'Developer Tools', 'A beginner-friendly guide to reading, formatting and validating JSON.', ['json-formatter', 'json-validator', 'json-to-xml-converter', 'xml-to-json-converter'], [
                ['Introduction', ['JSON is a lightweight data format used by APIs, apps, configuration files and databases. It is readable, but messy JSON can still be hard to inspect.', 'A formatter makes JSON easier to read. A validator checks whether the syntax is valid before you use it in code or an API request.']],
                ['Step-by-step guide', ['Paste JSON into the editor. Click validate first if you suspect an error, or beautify if the JSON is valid but compressed.', 'If validation fails, read the error, check the approximate line and look for missing commas, quotes, brackets or extra trailing commas.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['A compact API response may arrive as one long line. JSON Formatter can indent it so objects and arrays are easier to scan.', 'A broken config file may fail because one key is not quoted. JSON Validator helps identify where the syntax stops making sense.']],
                ['Tips for working with JSON', ['Use double quotes around keys and string values. Keep commas between items, but not after the last item in an object or array.', 'When debugging, reduce the JSON to a smaller sample. A small valid example is easier to repair than a giant broken payload.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['Common mistakes include trailing commas, single quotes, unquoted keys, missing braces and mixing comments into JSON. Standard JSON does not allow comments.', 'Another mistake is assuming formatted JSON is automatically correct. Formatting and validation are related but not identical.']],
                ['Beyond formatting', ['Once JSON is valid, you may need to convert it to XML, compare it with another payload or encode it for transport.', 'Toolexa includes JSON to XML and XML to JSON tools for simple browser-based conversions.']],
            ], [
                ['What is JSON formatting?', 'Formatting adds indentation and line breaks so JSON is easier to read.'],
                ['What does JSON validation check?', 'It checks whether the input follows valid JSON syntax.'],
                ['Are trailing commas allowed in JSON?', 'No, standard JSON does not allow trailing commas.'],
                ['Can JSON contain comments?', 'No, standard JSON does not support comments.'],
                ['Which Toolexa tools help with JSON?', 'Use JSON Formatter and JSON Validator.'],
            ]),
            self::article('Markdown vs HTML: Which Should You Use?', 'markdown-vs-html-which-should-you-use', 'Markdown vs HTML - Which Should You Use?', 'Compare Markdown and HTML for writing, formatting, web pages, documentation and content workflows.', 'Developer Tools', 'Choose the right format for documentation, articles and web content.', ['markdown-to-html-converter', 'html-to-markdown-converter', 'html-formatter'], [
                ['Introduction', ['Markdown and HTML both describe content, but they serve different levels of control. Markdown is lightweight and writer-friendly. HTML is detailed and browser-native.', 'The right choice depends on whether you value speed of writing or precise structure and presentation.']],
                ['Step-by-step guide', ['Choose Markdown for notes, README files, documentation drafts and simple articles. Choose HTML when you need exact tags, attributes, embeds, forms or layout hooks.', 'If you receive content in the wrong format, use Toolexa converters to move between HTML and Markdown for editing or publishing.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['A developer README is easier to maintain in Markdown. A landing page section with custom classes, buttons and embedded media needs HTML.', 'A writer may draft in Markdown, convert to HTML, then hand the HTML to a CMS or developer for final styling.']],
                ['Tips for clean content', ['Keep Markdown simple if it will be converted later. Avoid relying on platform-specific extensions unless the destination supports them.', 'For HTML, format the code before editing. Nested tags are easier to review when indentation is clear.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['A common mistake is expecting Markdown to control design like CSS and HTML. Markdown focuses on structure, not styling.', 'Another mistake is pasting messy HTML into documentation when a clean Markdown version would be easier to maintain.']],
                ['Choosing a workflow', ['Use Markdown for drafting and collaboration. Use HTML for final web structure when precision matters.', 'HTML Formatter, Markdown to HTML Converter and HTML to Markdown Converter make switching formats quicker.']],
            ], [
                ['Is Markdown easier than HTML?', 'For writing simple content, yes. Markdown is intentionally lightweight.'],
                ['Can Markdown replace HTML?', 'Not completely. HTML is needed for precise web structure and attributes.'],
                ['Can I convert Markdown to HTML?', 'Yes, use the Markdown to HTML Converter.'],
                ['Can I convert HTML back to Markdown?', 'Yes, use the HTML to Markdown Converter for common content structures.'],
                ['Which is better for README files?', 'Markdown is usually better for README files and documentation drafts.'],
            ]),
            self::article('Base64 Encoding Explained Simply', 'base64-encoding-explained-simply', 'Base64 Encoding Explained Simply', 'Understand Base64 encoding, decoding, common uses, limitations and how it differs from encryption and URL encoding.', 'Developer Tools', 'A plain-English explanation of Base64 for developers, students and curious users.', ['base64-encoder', 'base64-decoder', 'base64-encoder-decoder', 'image-to-base64-converter'], [
                ['Introduction', ['Base64 is a way to represent binary data using text characters. It appears in APIs, email attachments, data URLs and development debugging.', 'It is important to know that Base64 is encoding, not encryption. Anyone with the encoded text can usually decode it.']],
                ['Step-by-step guide', ['To encode, enter text or data and convert it into Base64 characters. To decode, paste valid Base64 and convert it back to readable text or original data where supported.', 'Use Base64 Encoder and Decoder for text, and Image to Base64 Converter when you need a data URL from an image.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['The word hello becomes a longer Base64 string. A small image can become a data URL that starts with a media type and Base64 content.', 'Developers often see Base64 in authorization headers, JSON payloads, email systems and embedded assets.']],
                ['Tips for using Base64', ['Use Base64 when a system expects text-safe representation. Avoid it for large files unless there is a clear reason because output becomes larger.', 'Never treat Base64 as secret storage. If the content is sensitive, use proper encryption or secure storage.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['The most common mistake is calling Base64 encrypted. It is reversible without a secret key.', 'Another mistake is copying incomplete Base64 text. Missing padding or broken characters can make decoding fail.']],
                ['Base64 versus URL encoding', ['URL encoding makes special characters safe inside URLs. Base64 represents binary or text data using a limited character set.', 'If you are fixing a query string, URL Encoder and Decoder may be the better tool.']],
            ], [
                ['Is Base64 secure?', 'No. Base64 is encoding, not encryption.'],
                ['Can Base64 be decoded?', 'Yes, valid Base64 can be decoded easily.'],
                ['Why is Base64 longer?', 'It represents data with text characters, which usually increases size.'],
                ['Can images be Base64 encoded?', 'Yes, use Image to Base64 Converter for image data URLs.'],
                ['When should I use URL encoding instead?', 'Use URL encoding for URLs, query strings and special URL characters.'],
            ]),
            self::article('How to Resize Images for Websites and Social Media', 'how-to-resize-images-for-websites-social-media', 'How to Resize Images for Websites and Social Media', 'Learn how to resize images for websites, blogs, profile pictures, thumbnails and social media without distortion.', 'Image Tools', 'Prepare images with the right dimensions for faster pages and cleaner posts.', ['image-resizer', 'image-cropper', 'image-compressor', 'color-picker-from-image'], [
                ['Introduction', ['Image resizing changes pixel dimensions. It helps images fit websites, forms, thumbnails, profile pictures and social media layouts without wasting file size.', 'Resizing is different from compression. Resizing changes width and height; compression reduces file weight. Often you need both.']],
                ['Step-by-step guide', ['Check the required size first. Upload the image, keep aspect ratio enabled when possible, enter the target width or height and preview the result.', 'After resizing, compress the image if file size is still high. Crop first if the important subject needs a different frame.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['A blog hero might need a wide image, while a profile picture usually needs a square crop. A product thumbnail may need consistent dimensions across a grid.', 'For social media, each platform has preferred ratios. When in doubt, crop to the intended ratio before resizing.']],
                ['Tips for sharp results', ['Do not enlarge tiny images too much. Upscaling can make them blurry because the missing detail is not really there.', 'Use original high-quality files when available, then export the final size needed by the website or platform.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['A common mistake is turning off aspect ratio and stretching faces or products. Another is uploading huge camera images directly to a website.', 'People also confuse file size with dimensions. A 300 KB image can still have unsuitable dimensions for a layout.']],
                ['Using related tools', ['Use Image Cropper for framing, Image Resizer for dimensions and Image Compressor for final file size.', 'Color Picker From Image can help sample brand colors from the image when preparing matching graphics.']],
            ], [
                ['What does resizing an image mean?', 'It means changing the pixel width and height of the image.'],
                ['Should I keep aspect ratio?', 'Usually yes, to avoid stretched or squeezed images.'],
                ['Is resizing the same as compression?', 'No. Resizing changes dimensions, while compression reduces file size.'],
                ['Can resizing improve page speed?', 'Yes, smaller dimensions can reduce unnecessary bandwidth.'],
                ['Which Toolexa tool resizes images?', 'Use the Image Resizer tool.'],
            ]),
            self::article('Complete Guide to Unit Conversion', 'complete-guide-to-unit-conversion', 'Complete Guide to Unit Conversion', 'Learn how unit conversion works for length, weight, temperature, volume and everyday measurement tasks.', 'Utility', 'A practical guide for converting measurements accurately in daily work.', ['unit-converter', 'percentage-calculator', 'random-number-generator'], [
                ['Introduction', ['Unit conversion changes a measurement from one unit to another while keeping the same real quantity. It appears in cooking, travel, construction, shopping, science and schoolwork.', 'The idea is simple, but mistakes happen when units look familiar or when metric and imperial systems mix.']],
                ['Step-by-step guide', ['Identify the quantity type first: length, weight, temperature, area, volume or speed. Then choose the source unit, enter the value and select the target unit.', 'After conversion, check whether the result is reasonable. A quick sense check catches many decimal-place errors.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['Converting kilometers to miles helps with travel distance. Converting kilograms to pounds helps with fitness or shipping. Celsius to Fahrenheit helps when reading weather or recipes from another region.', 'In schoolwork, unit conversion often matters before solving the main problem. Wrong units can make a correct formula produce a wrong answer.']],
                ['Tips for accuracy', ['Write units beside every number. Avoid copying only the value without the unit. For temperature, remember that conversion uses an offset, not only multiplication.', 'For professional work, confirm required precision. Construction, medicine and engineering may require stricter accuracy than everyday planning.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['A common mistake is converting area or volume like length. Square and cubic units scale differently.', 'Another mistake is rounding too early. Keep extra decimals during calculation, then round the final result for display.']],
                ['Using Unit Converter', ['Toolexa Unit Converter is useful for quick everyday conversions without building a spreadsheet.', 'For percentage-based comparisons after conversion, use Percentage Calculator to understand change, ratio or difference.']],
            ], [
                ['What is unit conversion?', 'It changes a measurement from one unit to another without changing the real quantity.'],
                ['Why do unit mistakes happen?', 'They often happen when systems mix or decimal places are misplaced.'],
                ['Is temperature conversion different?', 'Yes, temperature conversion includes an offset as well as scaling.'],
                ['Should I round converted values?', 'Round final results according to the precision needed for the task.'],
                ['Which tool converts units?', 'Use the Toolexa Unit Converter.'],
            ]),
            self::article('Percentage Calculator Guide with Real-Life Examples', 'percentage-calculator-guide-real-life-examples', 'Percentage Calculator Guide with Real-Life Examples', 'Learn percentage formulas for discounts, marks, profit, tax, change and everyday comparisons with practical examples.', 'Math', 'Understand percentages through real situations like shopping, marks and finance.', ['percentage-calculator', 'discount-calculator', 'gst-calculator', 'vat-calculator'], [
                ['Introduction', ['Percent means per hundred. It helps compare values of different sizes, calculate discounts, understand marks, estimate tax and measure growth or decline.', 'Percentages are common because they turn raw numbers into easy comparisons. A Rs. 100 increase means different things depending on the original amount.']],
                ['Step-by-step guide', ['To find a percentage of a number, multiply by the percentage and divide by 100. To find what percent one number is of another, divide part by whole and multiply by 100.', 'For percentage change, subtract old value from new value, divide by old value and multiply by 100.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['A 20 percent discount on Rs. 1,500 is Rs. 300, so the final price is Rs. 1,200. A student scoring 72 out of 80 has 90 percent.', 'If sales rise from 50 units to 65 units, the increase is 15 units, which is 30 percent of the original 50.']],
                ['Tips for everyday use', ['Always identify the base value. The same percentage can mean different amounts when the base changes.', 'In shopping, calculate discount first, then tax if tax applies after discount. In finance, confirm whether the rate is annual, monthly or one-time.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['A common mistake is reversing part and whole. Another is treating percentage points and percent change as the same thing.', 'For example, moving from 10 percent to 15 percent is a 5 percentage point increase, but a 50 percent relative increase.']],
                ['Using related calculators', ['Use Percentage Calculator for general math, Discount Calculator for sale prices, GST Calculator for Indian tax and VAT Calculator for value-added tax scenarios.', 'These tools make examples easier to test with your own numbers.']],
            ], [
                ['What does percent mean?', 'Percent means per hundred.'],
                ['How do I calculate 20 percent of a number?', 'Multiply the number by 20 and divide by 100.'],
                ['What is percentage change?', 'It measures increase or decrease compared with the original value.'],
                ['Are percent and percentage points the same?', 'No, percentage points describe direct difference between percentages.'],
                ['Which Toolexa tool helps?', 'Use the Percentage Calculator.'],
            ]),
            self::article('Age Calculator: More Than Just Finding Your Age', 'age-calculator-more-than-just-finding-your-age', 'Age Calculator - More Than Just Finding Your Age', 'Discover practical uses of an age calculator for forms, eligibility, anniversaries, education, records and date checks.', 'Utility', 'Use age calculation for forms, eligibility and date-based planning.', ['age-calculator', 'timestamp-converter', 'unit-converter'], [
                ['Introduction', ['An age calculator does more than count birthdays. It can help with eligibility checks, school forms, job applications, insurance records, medical forms and anniversary planning.', 'Manual age calculation gets tricky because months have different lengths and leap years exist. A calculator makes the result faster and clearer.']],
                ['Step-by-step guide', ['Enter the date of birth and the target date. If you want current age, use today as the target. Review years, months and days if the tool provides detailed output.', 'For official forms, copy the result carefully and confirm the required date format. Some forms use age as of a specific cutoff date, not today.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['School admissions often ask age as of a fixed date. Sports categories may use a season cutoff. Insurance and government forms may need exact age at application.', 'For personal use, age calculators can find time until a birthday, anniversary or milestone.']],
                ['Tips for date accuracy', ['Check date format before entering values. In some regions 05/06 means June 5; in others it means May 6.', 'If a deadline matters, calculate age as of that deadline, not as of the day you fill the form.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['A common mistake is using today when the form asks for age on a cutoff date. Another is mixing month and day order.', 'People also ignore leap-year birthdays. A calculator handles the calendar more reliably than mental math.']],
                ['Related date tools', ['Timestamp Converter is useful for developer-style dates and Unix timestamps, while Age Calculator is better for human age and date differences.', 'Unit Converter can help when a form asks related measurements in unfamiliar units.']],
            ], [
                ['What does an age calculator do?', 'It calculates age or date difference from a birth date to a target date.'],
                ['Why use a target date?', 'Some forms require age as of a specific cutoff date, not today.'],
                ['Can leap years affect age?', 'Yes, exact age calculation should account for leap years and month lengths.'],
                ['Is age only shown in years?', 'Many calculators also show months and days.'],
                ['Which Toolexa tool should I use?', 'Use the Age Calculator.'],
            ]),
            self::article('Barcode vs QR Code: Key Differences Explained', 'barcode-vs-qr-code-key-differences', 'Barcode vs QR Code - Key Differences Explained', 'Compare barcodes and QR codes by structure, data capacity, scanning, business uses and best practices.', 'Business Tools', 'Understand when to use a barcode and when a QR code is better.', ['barcode-generator', 'qr-generator'], [
                ['Introduction', ['Barcodes and QR codes both store machine-readable information, but they are built for different jobs. Traditional barcodes are usually one-dimensional, while QR codes are two-dimensional.', 'That structure affects data capacity, scanning direction, use cases and how much information can be stored.']],
                ['Step-by-step comparison', ['Use a barcode when you need product identification, inventory labels or retail scanning. Use a QR code when you need to open a URL, share text or connect offline material to online content.', 'Start with the scanner and destination system. A code is useful only if the people or machines around it can read it.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['A retail product may use EAN-13 or UPC-A for checkout. A warehouse shelf label may use Code128. A restaurant menu or event poster usually works better with a QR code.', 'Packaging can use both: barcode for inventory and QR code for customer-facing information.']],
                ['Tips for clean codes', ['Use high contrast, enough quiet space and correct size. Test printed codes with the actual scanner or phone that will be used.', 'For barcodes, choose the symbology required by the destination system. For QR codes, keep the URL short and mobile-friendly.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['A common mistake is using a QR code where a retail barcode is required. Another is printing codes too small or on curved reflective surfaces.', 'Businesses also forget to test after resizing artwork. Scaling can blur bars or modules and reduce scan reliability.']],
                ['Using Toolexa generators', ['Barcode Generator helps create Code128, Code39, EAN-13 and UPC-A codes. QR Code Generator helps create scannable codes for links or text.', 'Download and test the code before adding it to packaging, labels or print designs.']],
            ], [
                ['What is the main difference?', 'A barcode is often one-dimensional, while a QR code is two-dimensional and stores more data.'],
                ['Which is better for product checkout?', 'Retail checkout usually requires a standard barcode such as EAN or UPC.'],
                ['Which is better for website links?', 'QR codes are better for website links and phone scanning.'],
                ['Can packaging use both?', 'Yes, many products use barcodes for systems and QR codes for customers.'],
                ['Which Toolexa tools create them?', 'Use Barcode Generator and QR Code Generator.'],
            ]),
            self::article('Beginner\'s Guide to Color Codes (HEX, RGB & HSL)', 'beginners-guide-color-codes-hex-rgb-hsl', 'Beginner Guide to Color Codes - HEX, RGB and HSL', 'Learn HEX, RGB and HSL color codes with examples, conversion tips and practical web design usage.', 'Color Tools', 'A simple guide to the color formats used in CSS, design and branding.', ['hex-rgb-hsl-color-converter', 'color-picker-from-image', 'css-beautifier'], [
                ['Introduction', ['Digital colors are often written as HEX, RGB or HSL values. These formats describe the same idea in different ways so browsers, design tools and code can reproduce colors consistently.', 'Beginners often memorize one format without understanding when another is easier. HEX is compact, RGB is direct and HSL is intuitive for adjusting hue, saturation and lightness.']],
                ['Step-by-step guide', ['Use HEX when copying colors into CSS or design specs. Use RGB when working with red, green and blue channels. Use HSL when you want to make a color lighter, darker or less saturated.', 'The HEX RGB HSL Color Converter lets you move between formats and preview the color live.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['White is #ffffff or rgb(255, 255, 255). Black is #000000 or rgb(0, 0, 0). A brand blue might be stored as HEX in CSS and converted to HSL for creating hover states.', 'If you have a screenshot or product photo, Color Picker From Image can sample a pixel and report HEX, RGB and HSL values.']],
                ['Tips for better color work', ['Keep brand colors documented in more than one format. Use consistent names for CSS variables so teams do not copy random near-matches.', 'Check contrast between text and background. A beautiful color can still be hard to read if contrast is weak.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['A common mistake is forgetting the # in HEX or using invalid characters. Another is confusing RGB values with percentages.', 'People also create too many almost-identical colors. A small palette is easier to maintain than dozens of tiny variations.']],
                ['Using color tools', ['Use the converter for format changes, Color Picker From Image for sampling and CSS Beautifier for reading stylesheet color values more clearly.', 'Together, these tools help designers and developers move from visual color to usable code.']],
            ], [
                ['What is a HEX color?', 'HEX is a compact color code commonly used in CSS, such as #3366ff.'],
                ['What does RGB mean?', 'RGB describes red, green and blue channel values.'],
                ['What is HSL useful for?', 'HSL is useful for adjusting hue, saturation and lightness.'],
                ['Can I convert HEX to RGB?', 'Yes, use the HEX RGB HSL Color Converter.'],
                ['Can I pick colors from an image?', 'Yes, use Color Picker From Image.'],
            ]),
            self::article('What is PPF? Complete Guide with Interest Calculation', 'what-is-ppf-complete-guide-with-interest-calculation', 'What is PPF? Complete Guide with Interest Calculation', 'Learn what PPF is, how PPF interest is calculated on monthly balances, lock-in rules and how to project maturity value with a calculator.', 'Finance', 'Understand how the Public Provident Fund works and how yearly compounding builds long-term savings.', ['ppf-calculator', 'compound-interest-calculator', 'sip-calculator'], [
                ['What is PPF', ['The Public Provident Fund is a long-term government-backed savings scheme popular with Indian savers who want a conservative, tax-friendly option outside the stock market. It has a fixed lock-in period, and the interest rate is reviewed periodically by the government rather than fixed for the entire term.', 'Because PPF rewards patience rather than large deposits, it works best as a long-term corner of a financial plan, not a short-term parking spot for money you may need soon.']],
                ['How PPF interest is calculated', ['Interest is generally calculated on the lowest balance held in the account between the fifth day and the last day of each month, then compounded and credited once a year. This is why the deposit date inside the month can matter more than most people expect.', 'Depositing early in the month, ideally before the fifth, means that month\'s contribution starts earning interest immediately instead of being excluded from that month\'s interest calculation.']],
                ['Practical example of PPF growth', ['Consider a saver who contributes a fixed amount every month for fifteen years at an illustrative annual rate. Because interest compounds yearly and is added back to the principal, the growth curve becomes steeper in the later years compared with the early years.', 'The PPF Calculator lets you enter a monthly or yearly contribution and an assumed rate to see a projected maturity value, so you can compare a few contribution levels before committing to one.']],
                ['Tips for maximizing PPF returns', ['Try to deposit before the fifth of the month so that month is included in interest calculation. Keep contributions consistent every year rather than depositing a lump sum only when convenient.', 'After the initial lock-in period ends, the account can usually be extended in blocks of years, with or without further contributions. Decide early which path fits your goal so you are not deciding under time pressure.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['A frequent mistake is depositing late in the month and losing that month from interest calculation. Another is missing the minimum yearly deposit required to keep the account active, which can lead to a lapsed account and reactivation charges.', 'Some savers also forget the extension choice at maturity and withdraw everything by default, even when continuing would have suited their goal better.']],
                ['When to use the PPF Calculator', ['Use it to compare monthly versus yearly contribution patterns, to project maturity value at different assumed rates, and to see how an extension period changes the final corpus.', 'Pair it with the Compound Interest Calculator to understand the mechanics of yearly compounding, and with the SIP Calculator when comparing PPF against a market-linked monthly investment.']],
            ], [
                ['Is PPF a safe investment?', 'It is a government-backed scheme generally viewed as conservative, though returns depend on the rate declared for each period.'],
                ['What is the lock-in period for PPF?', 'The scheme has a fixed multi-year lock-in and can typically be extended afterward in blocks of years.'],
                ['Does the deposit date affect interest?', 'Yes, interest is usually based on the lowest balance between the fifth and last day of the month.'],
                ['Can I withdraw from PPF before maturity?', 'Partial withdrawal is generally allowed after a few years, subject to scheme conditions.'],
                ['Which tool helps estimate PPF maturity?', 'Use the PPF Calculator to project maturity value from your contribution plan.'],
            ], '2026-07-15'),
            self::article('EPF Explained: Everything Employees Should Know', 'epf-explained-everything-employees-should-know', 'EPF Explained: Everything Employees Should Know', 'Understand how EPF contributions work, how employer and employee shares are calculated and how to estimate retirement corpus.', 'Finance', 'A clear explanation of how salaried employees build retirement savings through EPF.', ['epf-calculator', 'ppf-calculator', 'nps-calculator'], [
                ['What is EPF', ['The Employees Provident Fund is a retirement savings scheme for salaried employees, where a share of basic pay is contributed every month, usually matched by an employer contribution. Over a working career, this builds into a substantial retirement corpus.', 'Unlike a voluntary scheme, EPF contributions are typically automatic through payroll, which makes it one of the more consistent long-term savings habits an employee has without needing to remember to invest.']],
                ['How EPF contributions are calculated', ['A percentage of basic salary plus dearness allowance is contributed by the employee, with a broadly similar contribution from the employer, part of which may be directed toward a linked pension component rather than the provident fund balance itself.', 'The EPF Calculator lets you enter basic salary, contribution percentage and expected service years to estimate how the balance can grow with regular monthly additions and periodic interest credit.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['An employee with a moderate basic salary contributing consistently for two decades can accumulate a meaningful corpus purely from the combination of steady contributions and yearly interest credit, even without any lump-sum deposits.', 'Comparing two scenarios, one with a salary increment every few years and one without, shows how rising basic pay compounds the benefit, since higher basic pay means higher rupee contributions in later years.']],
                ['Tips for employees', ['Track your EPF passbook periodically to confirm contributions are being deposited correctly and on time by the employer. Keep your account linked to a verified identifier so past employer contributions merge into one account when you switch jobs.', 'Avoid withdrawing EPF balance at every job change. Transferring the balance to the new employer preserves continuity and keeps the compounding effect uninterrupted.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['A common mistake is withdrawing the full EPF balance during a job transition instead of transferring it, which resets the compounding benefit and can affect eligibility for related benefits.', 'Employees also sometimes ignore mismatches between salary slips and passbook entries. Checking periodically catches missed or delayed employer contributions early.']],
                ['Using EPF alongside other schemes', ['EPF is usually the base layer of retirement savings for a salaried employee. Many people add PPF for additional tax-friendly long-term saving or NPS for a market-linked retirement option with different withdrawal rules.', 'Use the EPF Calculator for a payroll-based projection, then compare it with PPF Calculator and NPS Calculator outputs to see how the three pieces fit together for retirement planning.']],
            ], [
                ['What is EPF?', 'EPF is a retirement savings scheme for salaried employees funded by monthly employee and employer contributions.'],
                ['Is EPF contribution compulsory?', 'For most eligible salaried employees under applicable rules, contribution is generally mandatory through payroll.'],
                ['What happens to EPF when I change jobs?', 'The balance can usually be transferred to a new account linked to the new employer instead of being withdrawn.'],
                ['Does EPF earn interest?', 'Yes, interest is credited periodically based on the rate declared for that period.'],
                ['Which tool estimates EPF growth?', 'Use the EPF Calculator to project your retirement corpus from salary and contribution inputs.'],
            ], '2026-07-15'),
            self::article('NPS vs PPF vs EPF: Complete Comparison', 'nps-vs-ppf-vs-epf-complete-comparison', 'NPS vs PPF vs EPF: Complete Comparison', 'Compare NPS, PPF and EPF by risk, returns, lock-in, contribution style and suitability for retirement and long-term goals.', 'Finance', 'A side-by-side look at three popular long-term saving options for Indian earners.', ['nps-calculator', 'ppf-calculator', 'epf-calculator', 'sip-calculator'], [
                ['Introduction', ['NPS, PPF and EPF are three of the most common long-term savings options available to Indian earners, but they are built differently. EPF is payroll-linked, PPF is voluntary and conservative, and NPS is market-linked with its own withdrawal structure.', 'Understanding the differences helps you decide which one deserves extra voluntary contributions once your mandatory EPF share is already being deducted.']],
                ['Step-by-step comparison', ['Start with who can contribute. EPF generally applies to salaried employees through an employer. PPF is open to most individuals regardless of employment type. NPS is open to both salaried and self-employed people with a choice of contribution amount.', 'Next compare structure: EPF and PPF returns are typically declared periodically and applied more predictably, while NPS returns depend on the mix of equity and debt funds chosen, which introduces market-linked variability.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['A salaried employee already contributing to EPF might add PPF for additional tax-friendly conservative saving, or add NPS for market exposure and a distinct retirement withdrawal structure with its own rules.', 'A self-employed person without EPF access might rely on PPF for stability and NPS for growth potential, adjusting the equity-debt mix in NPS based on age and risk comfort.']],
                ['Tips for choosing an allocation', ['Do not treat these three as competing options only. Many long-term plans use a combination: EPF as the automatic base, PPF for conservative voluntary saving, and NPS for market-linked growth with tax-related benefits under applicable rules.', 'Revisit the mix every few years as income, risk comfort and time to retirement change, rather than setting an allocation once and never reviewing it.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['A common mistake is comparing NPS returns and PPF returns as if both carry identical risk. NPS includes market-linked components, while PPF is typically more predictable.', 'Another mistake is ignoring withdrawal rules. NPS has structured withdrawal and annuity requirements at retirement that differ meaningfully from PPF maturity or EPF withdrawal rules.']],
                ['Using the calculators together', ['Use the EPF Calculator for your payroll-based base corpus, the PPF Calculator for voluntary conservative contributions, and the NPS Calculator for market-linked projections under different equity-debt assumptions.', 'The SIP Calculator can help you separately model any additional mutual fund investing outside these three retirement-focused schemes.']],
            ], [
                ['Which is better, NPS or PPF?', 'NPS offers market-linked growth potential while PPF offers more predictable conservative returns. The better option depends on risk comfort and goals.'],
                ['Can I contribute to all three?', 'Yes, many earners contribute to EPF through payroll while voluntarily adding PPF and NPS.'],
                ['Which has the longest lock-in?', 'PPF has a fixed multi-year lock-in, while NPS is generally structured around retirement age withdrawal rules.'],
                ['Is EPF only for salaried employees?', 'Yes, EPF is typically linked to employer payroll contributions.'],
                ['Which calculator should I use to compare all three?', 'Use the NPS, PPF and EPF calculators together, then compare projected outcomes side by side.'],
            ], '2026-07-15'),
            self::article('CAGR Explained with Practical Investment Examples', 'cagr-explained-with-practical-investment-examples', 'CAGR Explained with Practical Investment Examples', 'Learn what CAGR means, how to calculate compound annual growth rate and how to use it to compare investments fairly.', 'Finance', 'Understand how CAGR smooths out yearly ups and downs into one comparable growth figure.', ['cagr-calculator', 'sip-calculator', 'compound-interest-calculator'], [
                ['What is CAGR', ['Compound Annual Growth Rate expresses the growth of an investment as if it had grown at a smooth, steady annual rate, even though the real journey usually included up and down years. It answers one question clearly: what constant yearly rate would have produced this same final result?', 'CAGR is useful precisely because real returns are rarely a straight line. It lets you compare two investments held for different durations on a single, consistent yearly basis.']],
                ['Step-by-step guide', ['To calculate CAGR, you need the starting value, the ending value and the number of years between them. Divide the ending value by the starting value, raise the result to the power of one divided by the number of years, then subtract one.', 'The CAGR Calculator handles this formula directly, so you only need to enter the starting amount, ending amount and holding period to get an annualized growth figure.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['If an investment grew from a starting amount to roughly double over eight years, the CAGR would land in a moderate range even though some individual years may have grown faster or shrunk compared with others.', 'Comparing two funds held for different periods only makes sense once both are converted to CAGR. A fund held for three years cannot be compared directly with one held for ten years using total return alone.']],
                ['Tips for using CAGR wisely', ['CAGR describes the past. It does not guarantee that future years will follow the same smooth path, so treat it as a historical summary rather than a forecast.', 'When comparing investment options, check the exact time period used for each CAGR figure. A short favorable period can produce a much higher CAGR than a longer, more representative period.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['A common mistake is applying CAGR to an investment with irregular contributions, such as a SIP, where money was added at different times rather than once at the start.', 'Another mistake is comparing CAGR figures calculated over different time windows as if they represent the same thing, which can make a short lucky period look better than a longer track record.']],
                ['When calculators help', ['Use the CAGR Calculator for lump-sum growth between two dates, the SIP Calculator for regular monthly contributions with an assumed return, and the Compound Interest Calculator to see year-by-year compounding in detail.', 'Together these tools help you move from a single confusing return percentage to a clearer picture of how an investment actually grew.']],
            ], [
                ['What does CAGR stand for?', 'CAGR stands for Compound Annual Growth Rate.'],
                ['Is CAGR the same as annual return?', 'Not exactly. CAGR smooths fluctuating yearly returns into one steady annualized figure.'],
                ['Can CAGR be used for SIP investments?', 'CAGR is best suited to lump-sum growth. SIP returns are usually better measured with a different annualized method that accounts for staggered contributions.'],
                ['Does a higher CAGR always mean a better investment?', 'Not necessarily. Risk, consistency and the time period used should also be considered.'],
                ['Which tool calculates CAGR quickly?', 'Use the CAGR Calculator with starting value, ending value and duration.'],
            ], '2026-07-15'),
            self::article('How to Calculate Inflation Rate Easily', 'how-to-calculate-inflation-rate-easily', 'How to Calculate Inflation Rate Easily', 'Learn the simple formula for calculating inflation rate between two periods, with practical examples and common pitfalls.', 'Finance', 'A straightforward walkthrough of the inflation rate formula and how to apply it to real prices.', ['inflation-calculator', 'percentage-calculator', 'cagr-calculator'], [
                ['What the inflation rate measures', ['The inflation rate measures how much the general price level has changed between two points in time, usually expressed as a percentage. A positive figure means prices rose on average; a negative figure, though less common, means prices fell.', 'Individual items can rise or fall differently from the overall rate, which is why inflation is normally reported using a basket of goods and services rather than a single product price.']],
                ['Step-by-step guide', ['To calculate the inflation rate between two periods, subtract the earlier price index or price value from the later one, divide by the earlier value, and multiply by one hundred.', 'The Inflation Calculator automates this so you can enter a starting price and an ending price, or a starting price and an assumed annual rate, to see how costs move over time.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['If a monthly grocery basket cost a certain amount last year and a higher amount this year, applying the formula converts that difference into a clear percentage you can compare against wage growth or savings returns.', 'Over a longer stretch, small annual increases compound. A modest yearly rate applied consistently for a decade can meaningfully raise the future cost of a goal like education or a large purchase.']],
                ['Tips for accurate calculations', ['Use consistent items or a consistent basket when comparing two periods. Comparing unrelated products will not produce a meaningful inflation figure.', 'When projecting forward, treat the assumed rate as an estimate, not a guarantee, and revisit it periodically as real prices become available.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['A frequent mistake is confusing a single product price change with the broader inflation rate, which reflects a wider basket of goods and services.', 'Another mistake is ignoring compounding when projecting several years forward. Multiplying a single year rate by the number of years understates the true future cost compared with compounding it year over year.']],
                ['Using related tools', ['Use the Inflation Calculator to project future costs, the Percentage Calculator to work out the raw percentage change between two prices, and the CAGR Calculator when you want an annualized growth figure from historical price data.', 'Together these tools turn a vague sense that "things cost more now" into a specific number you can plan around.']],
            ], [
                ['What is the basic inflation rate formula?', 'Subtract the earlier value from the later value, divide by the earlier value, then multiply by one hundred.'],
                ['Can inflation be negative?', 'Yes, a broad fall in prices is sometimes called deflation, though sustained inflation is more common historically.'],
                ['How is inflation different from a single price increase?', 'Inflation reflects a wider basket of goods and services, not one product alone.'],
                ['Why does inflation matter for savings?', 'It reduces purchasing power if returns on savings do not keep pace with rising prices.'],
                ['Which tool helps calculate inflation quickly?', 'Use the Inflation Calculator to compare prices across two periods or project future costs.'],
            ], '2026-07-15'),
            self::article('Complete Guide to Loan EMI Calculations', 'complete-guide-to-loan-emi-calculations', 'Complete Guide to Loan EMI Calculations', 'Understand the EMI formula, how principal and interest split changes over time and how to compare loan offers using an EMI calculator.', 'Finance', 'A deep dive into how EMI is calculated across home, car, personal and general loans.', ['emi-calculator', 'loan-calculator', 'home-loan-emi-calculator', 'car-loan-emi-calculator'], [
                ['How EMI is calculated', ['EMI is calculated from three inputs: the loan amount, the annual interest rate and the tenure in months. The formula converts the annual rate into a monthly rate and produces a fixed payment that fully repays the loan by the end of the tenure.', 'While the formula itself is fixed, small changes in any one input can shift the EMI meaningfully, which is why testing scenarios matters more than memorizing the formula.']],
                ['Step-by-step guide across loan types', ['For any loan type, start with the same three inputs, then use the calculator that matches your loan category. Home, car and personal loans often carry different typical rates and tenures even though the underlying formula is identical.', 'Compare at least two tenure options for the same loan amount so you can see the trade-off between a lower monthly payment and a higher total interest cost.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['A shorter tenure on the same loan amount produces a higher EMI but lower total interest paid over the life of the loan. A longer tenure lowers the EMI but usually increases the total interest paid.', 'Two loans with the same EMI can still differ significantly in total cost if their interest rates or tenures are different, which is why total repayment should always be checked alongside EMI.']],
                ['Tips for smarter loan decisions', ['Always look at total interest paid, not only the monthly figure. A comfortable EMI today should not come from stretching tenure so far that the loan becomes expensive overall.', 'Check for prepayment options. Making occasional extra payments toward principal, where allowed without heavy penalty, can meaningfully reduce total interest.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['A common mistake is comparing EMI across lenders without confirming that the compared loan amount, tenure and fees are identical. Differences in any of these make EMI comparisons misleading.', 'Borrowers also sometimes ignore how the interest-to-principal ratio shifts across the tenure, assuming each EMI payment reduces the loan by an equal amount, which is not how amortizing loans work.']],
                ['Choosing the right calculator', ['Use the general EMI Calculator or Loan Calculator for a quick estimate, then switch to Home Loan EMI Calculator or Car Loan EMI Calculator when you want assumptions closer to that specific loan category.', 'Running the same loan amount through more than one tenure scenario before applying is the single most useful habit for avoiding regret later.']],
            ], [
                ['What three inputs does EMI depend on?', 'Loan amount, annual interest rate and tenure.'],
                ['Does a lower EMI always mean a cheaper loan?', 'Not necessarily. A lower EMI from a longer tenure can increase total interest paid.'],
                ['Is the EMI formula the same for every loan type?', 'Yes, the underlying formula is the same, though typical rates and tenures vary by loan type.'],
                ['Can prepayment reduce my EMI or tenure?', 'Prepayment can reduce outstanding principal, which may shorten tenure or lower future EMI, subject to lender rules.'],
                ['Which calculator should I start with?', 'Start with the EMI Calculator, then use the category-specific calculator that matches your loan.'],
            ], '2026-07-15'),
            self::article('Car Loan vs Personal Loan: Which One Should You Choose?', 'car-loan-vs-personal-loan-which-one-to-choose', 'Car Loan vs Personal Loan: Which One Should You Choose?', 'Compare car loans and personal loans by interest rate, tenure, collateral and flexibility to decide the better option for buying a vehicle.', 'Finance', 'A practical comparison for anyone deciding how to finance a vehicle purchase.', ['car-loan-emi-calculator', 'personal-loan-emi-calculator', 'emi-calculator'], [
                ['Introduction', ['Car loans and personal loans can both fund a vehicle purchase, but they are structured differently. A car loan is usually secured against the vehicle itself, while a personal loan is typically unsecured and can be used for any purpose.', 'That structural difference tends to affect interest rate, maximum loan amount and how quickly the loan can be closed if you sell the vehicle later.']],
                ['Step-by-step comparison', ['Start by comparing the interest rate each option offers for your situation, since secured car loans often carry a different rate profile than unsecured personal loans. Then compare maximum tenure, since longer tenures reduce EMI but increase total interest.', 'Check what happens if you want to sell the vehicle before the loan is repaid. A car loan usually ties the vehicle to the lender until closure, while a personal loan does not create that direct link.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['Financing a mid-range car through a secured car loan may offer a lower EMI for the same tenure compared with an unsecured personal loan of the same amount, because the vehicle itself backs the loan.', 'Someone who wants full ownership flexibility from day one, without the vehicle being linked to the loan, may still prefer a personal loan despite a potentially higher rate.']],
                ['Tips for choosing', ['If minimizing interest cost is the priority and you are comfortable with the vehicle backing the loan, a car loan is often the more cost-efficient route for financing a vehicle specifically.', 'If you want flexibility, a shorter approval process, or plan to use part of the funds for non-vehicle expenses like insurance or accessories, a personal loan may fit better despite a possibly higher rate.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['A common mistake is comparing only the advertised rate without checking processing fees, which can differ meaningfully between secured and unsecured loans.', 'Buyers also sometimes choose a personal loan purely for convenience without calculating how much extra interest that convenience costs over the full tenure.']],
                ['Using the calculators', ['Use the Car Loan EMI Calculator to estimate secured loan payments for a specific vehicle price, and the Personal Loan EMI Calculator to see the unsecured alternative for the same amount and tenure.', 'Run both through the same loan amount and tenure so the comparison reflects only the rate and structure difference, not mismatched assumptions.']],
            ], [
                ['Which usually has a lower interest rate, car loan or personal loan?', 'Car loans are typically secured against the vehicle and can carry a different, often lower, rate profile than unsecured personal loans, though this varies by lender.'],
                ['Can I use a personal loan to buy a car?', 'Yes, personal loans are generally unrestricted in use and can fund a vehicle purchase.'],
                ['What happens to a car loan if I sell the vehicle early?', 'The loan is usually linked to the vehicle and needs to be settled or transferred as part of the sale process.'],
                ['Is a personal loan faster to get approved?', 'It can be, since it typically does not require vehicle-specific documentation, though this depends on the lender.'],
                ['Which calculator should I use to compare both?', 'Use the Car Loan EMI Calculator and Personal Loan EMI Calculator side by side with the same amount and tenure.'],
            ], '2026-07-15'),
            self::article('Education Loan Guide for Students', 'education-loan-guide-for-students', 'Education Loan Guide for Students', 'Learn how education loans work, how EMI is calculated after the moratorium period and how to plan repayment during and after studies.', 'Finance', 'A student-friendly explanation of education loan structure, EMI and repayment timing.', ['education-loan-emi-calculator', 'emi-calculator', 'loan-calculator'], [
                ['Introduction', ['Education loans help students fund tuition, accommodation and related costs when upfront savings are not enough. They are structured differently from many other loans because repayment often does not begin immediately.', 'Most education loans include a moratorium period covering the study duration plus a short window afterward, during which the student is not required to make full EMI payments.']],
                ['Step-by-step guide', ['Start by estimating the total loan amount needed across the full course duration, not just the first year. Then check the moratorium period offered and whether interest accrues during that time.', 'Once the moratorium ends, use an EMI calculator with the accumulated loan amount, including any interest added during the study period, to estimate the actual monthly repayment that will begin.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['A student borrowing for a multi-year course may see the loan balance grow during the moratorium if interest accrues and is added to principal, meaning EMI is calculated on a higher amount than originally borrowed.', 'Comparing a loan with interest-only payments during the study period against one with no payments at all shows how much moratorium terms can affect the final EMI once repayment starts.']],
                ['Tips for students and families', ['If possible, pay at least the accruing interest during the study period. This keeps the principal from growing and can noticeably reduce the EMI once full repayment begins.', 'Plan repayment timing around expected job placement. Some loans allow the moratorium to extend a short period after course completion specifically for this reason.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['A common mistake is calculating EMI only on the amount initially disbursed, ignoring interest that may accrue and compound during the moratorium period.', 'Families also sometimes underestimate total course cost, requiring a second loan or top-up later instead of planning for the full amount upfront.']],
                ['Using the calculators', ['Use the Education Loan EMI Calculator to model repayment starting after the moratorium, factoring in any interest accrued during the study years, and compare it against the general EMI Calculator for a simpler estimate.', 'Loan Calculator can help model total repayment across the full loan life, including the moratorium period, for a fuller planning picture.']],
            ], [
                ['What is a moratorium period in an education loan?', 'It is a period, usually covering the study duration and a short time after, during which full EMI repayment is not required.'],
                ['Does interest accrue during the moratorium?', 'Often yes, depending on the lender, and it may be added to the principal, increasing future EMI.'],
                ['Should I pay interest during my studies if I can?', 'Paying accruing interest during the moratorium can reduce the EMI burden once full repayment starts.'],
                ['Can the loan amount cover living expenses too?', 'Many education loans can cover tuition plus related costs like accommodation, depending on the lender and course.'],
                ['Which calculator estimates education loan EMI?', 'Use the Education Loan EMI Calculator for a repayment estimate after the moratorium period.'],
            ], '2026-07-15'),
            self::article('Gold Loan Explained: Benefits, Risks & EMI Calculation', 'gold-loan-explained-benefits-risks-emi-calculation', 'Gold Loan Explained: Benefits, Risks and EMI Calculation', 'Understand how gold loans work, their benefits, risks of default, interest calculation and how to estimate EMI before borrowing.', 'Finance', 'A practical look at borrowing against gold, including EMI planning and key risks.', ['gold-loan-calculator', 'emi-calculator', 'percentage-calculator'], [
                ['What is a gold loan', ['A gold loan is a secured loan where gold jewelry or coins are pledged as collateral in exchange for funds, usually processed faster than many unsecured loans because the collateral simplifies approval.', 'The loan amount is typically based on a percentage of the assessed value of the pledged gold, which means the loan amount you qualify for depends directly on the gold you offer.']],
                ['Step-by-step guide', ['Start by getting the gold appraised to understand its assessed value, since the loan offer will be based on a percentage of this value rather than the full market price.', 'Once you know the potential loan amount, use a gold loan calculator with the interest rate and tenure offered to estimate EMI, or explore an interest-only repayment option if the lender allows it.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['A borrower pledging gold valued at a certain assessed amount may be offered a loan up to a percentage of that value, with EMI calculated the same way as any other secured loan once rate and tenure are set.', 'Some gold loans offer a bullet repayment structure, where interest is paid periodically and the principal is repaid at the end, which produces a very different cash flow than a standard EMI schedule.']],
                ['Tips for borrowing safely', ['Compare the interest rate and processing charges across a few lenders, since gold loan rates can vary. Also confirm the exact valuation method used to assess your gold.', 'Keep track of the repayment schedule closely. Because the loan is secured by a physical asset with personal value, missed payments carry a real risk of losing the pledged gold.']],
                ['Common mistakes and risks', ['The biggest risk is default, since failure to repay can lead to the lender auctioning the pledged gold to recover the loan amount, meaning a loan default has a very direct cost.', 'Another mistake is borrowing more than needed simply because a higher amount was approved. A larger loan means a larger EMI or a larger bullet repayment obligation.']],
                ['Using the calculators', ['Use the Gold Loan Calculator to estimate EMI or interest-only payments based on the loan amount, rate and tenure, and the Percentage Calculator to quickly check what percentage of your gold value the loan offer represents.', 'The general EMI Calculator is useful for comparing a gold loan EMI structure against another secured or unsecured loan for the same amount.']],
            ], [
                ['What is used as collateral in a gold loan?', 'Gold jewelry or coins are pledged as collateral against the loan amount.'],
                ['How is the gold loan amount decided?', 'It is typically based on a percentage of the assessed value of the pledged gold.'],
                ['What happens if I miss repayments?', 'The lender may have the right to auction the pledged gold to recover the outstanding loan amount, so missed payments carry real risk.'],
                ['Is EMI the only repayment option for gold loans?', 'No, some lenders offer interest-only periodic payments with principal due at the end, in addition to standard EMI.'],
                ['Which tool helps estimate gold loan repayment?', 'Use the Gold Loan Calculator for EMI or interest-only repayment estimates.'],
            ], '2026-07-15'),
            self::article('GST Inclusive vs GST Exclusive: Explained with Examples', 'gst-inclusive-vs-gst-exclusive-explained', 'GST Inclusive vs GST Exclusive: Explained with Examples', 'Understand the difference between GST inclusive and GST exclusive pricing, with formulas and examples for invoices and receipts.', 'Finance', 'Learn exactly when to add GST to a price and when to extract it from a total.', ['gst-calculator', 'percentage-calculator', 'vat-calculator'], [
                ['What inclusive and exclusive pricing mean', ['A GST-exclusive price is the taxable value before tax is added, meaning the final amount a customer pays will be higher once GST is applied on top of it.', 'A GST-inclusive price already contains the tax within the displayed figure, meaning the taxable value and the GST amount are both hidden inside that single number until you extract them.']],
                ['Step-by-step guide', ['For an exclusive amount, multiply the base value by the GST rate and add that result to the base value to get the final price a customer pays.', 'For an inclusive amount, divide the final price by one plus the GST rate expressed as a decimal to find the taxable value, then subtract that from the final price to find the GST amount.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['A service listed at a certain exclusive price with an eighteen percent GST rate will show a noticeably higher final invoice amount once tax is added on top.', 'A retail receipt that shows only a final inclusive amount requires the reverse calculation, dividing by one plus the rate, to figure out exactly how much of that total was tax versus the actual cost of the item.']],
                ['Tips for accurate invoicing', ['Always label whether a quoted price is inclusive or exclusive, since the same number can represent two very different actual costs depending on which it is.', 'When comparing prices from different sellers, confirm both are quoting the same basis. An exclusive price from one seller can look cheaper than an inclusive price from another while actually costing more after tax.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['The most common mistake is applying GST on top of a price that already includes tax, effectively taxing the amount twice.', 'Another mistake is using the exclusive formula on an inclusive amount, which produces a GST figure that is too high because it is calculated on the wrong base value.']],
                ['Using GST tools', ['Use the GST Calculator to switch between inclusive and exclusive modes instantly instead of manually rearranging the formula each time.', 'The Percentage Calculator is useful for a quick sanity check on the raw percentage relationship, and the VAT Calculator applies the same inclusive-exclusive logic for value-added tax scenarios outside India.']],
            ], [
                ['What is the main difference between GST inclusive and exclusive?', 'Exclusive pricing adds GST on top of a base value, while inclusive pricing already contains GST within the final amount.'],
                ['How do I remove GST from an inclusive price?', 'Divide the inclusive price by one plus the GST rate as a decimal, then subtract that result from the original amount to get the GST portion.'],
                ['Why do invoices sometimes show a much higher total than the listed price?', 'Because the listed price was GST exclusive, and tax was added afterward to reach the final invoice total.'],
                ['Can the same GST calculator handle both modes?', 'Yes, the GST Calculator supports switching between inclusive and exclusive calculation modes.'],
                ['Does this same logic apply outside India?', 'A similar inclusive-exclusive relationship applies to VAT in many other countries, handled by the VAT Calculator.'],
            ], '2026-07-15'),
            self::article('Beginner\'s Guide to JSON Formatting and Validation', 'beginners-guide-to-json-formatting-and-validation', 'Beginner\'s Guide to JSON Formatting and Validation', 'A practical beginner walkthrough of formatting, validating and minifying JSON, with common syntax errors explained simply.', 'Developer Tools', 'Learn the difference between formatting, validating and minifying JSON with hands-on examples.', ['json-formatter', 'json-validator', 'json-minifier'], [
                ['Why JSON trips up beginners', ['JSON looks simple at first glance, but small punctuation slips like a missing comma or an extra bracket can make an entire file unreadable to a program, even though it still looks fine to a human eye at a quick glance.', 'The three tasks that confuse beginners most are formatting, which only changes spacing, validating, which checks correctness, and minifying, which removes spacing entirely for smaller file size. They sound similar but do different jobs.']],
                ['Step-by-step guide', ['If you are unsure whether JSON is valid, start with a validator before doing anything else. Fix any reported errors first, since formatting broken JSON usually just makes broken JSON look neat.', 'Once the JSON is confirmed valid, use a formatter to add indentation for readability during development, or a minifier to strip whitespace when preparing a smaller payload for production use.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['A configuration file that fails to load might contain a single unquoted key. Running it through a validator usually points to roughly where the structure breaks, which is faster than scanning every line manually.', 'An API response saved as one long unreadable line becomes much easier to review once passed through a formatter, revealing the nested objects and arrays clearly.']],
                ['Tips for beginners', ['Learn to recognize the four common failure points: missing commas between items, trailing commas after the last item, unquoted keys, and mismatched brackets or braces.', 'Keep a small, valid JSON snippet handy as a reference. Comparing your broken file against a known-good example makes it much easier to spot exactly where the structure diverges.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['Standard JSON does not support comments, so any file with explanatory text inside double slashes or hash symbols will fail validation immediately.', 'Beginners also often confuse single quotes with double quotes. JSON strictly requires double quotes around keys and string values, not single quotes.']],
                ['Formatting, validating and minifying together', ['Use JSON Validator first to confirm correctness, JSON Formatter to make the structure readable during editing, and JSON Minifier when the final payload needs to be as small as possible for transport.', 'Getting comfortable moving between all three tools, rather than relying on only one, is what separates a confident JSON workflow from a frustrating one.']],
            ], [
                ['What is the difference between formatting and validating JSON?', 'Formatting changes spacing and indentation for readability, while validating checks whether the JSON syntax is actually correct.'],
                ['Why does my JSON fail validation even though it looks fine?', 'Small issues like trailing commas, single quotes or unquoted keys are easy to miss visually but still break strict JSON syntax.'],
                ['What does minifying JSON do?', 'It removes unnecessary whitespace and line breaks to reduce file size, without changing the data itself.'],
                ['Can JSON include comments?', 'No, standard JSON syntax does not support comments of any kind.'],
                ['Which Toolexa tools help with JSON basics?', 'Use JSON Validator, JSON Formatter and JSON Minifier for the three core JSON tasks.'],
            ], '2026-07-15'),
            self::article('XML vs JSON: Key Differences Explained', 'xml-vs-json-key-differences-explained', 'XML vs JSON: Key Differences Explained', 'Compare XML and JSON by syntax, readability, data types and typical use cases, with conversion tips between the two.', 'Developer Tools', 'Understand when XML makes sense and when JSON is the simpler choice.', ['json-to-xml-converter', 'xml-to-json-converter', 'csv-to-json-converter'], [
                ['Introduction', ['XML and JSON both describe structured data, but they come from different design philosophies. XML uses tags similar to HTML, while JSON uses a more compact key-value structure closer to how many programming languages represent objects.', 'Neither format is universally better. The right choice usually depends on the systems you are integrating with, since many established enterprise systems still expect XML while most modern web APIs default to JSON.']],
                ['Step-by-step comparison', ['Look at verbosity first. XML requires opening and closing tags for every element, which makes files larger, while JSON typically expresses the same data more compactly using brackets and colons.', 'Then consider data types. JSON has native support for numbers, booleans, arrays and null values, while XML represents everything as text unless a schema is layered on top to define types explicitly.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['A configuration document from an older enterprise system is more likely to arrive in XML, while a response from a modern REST API is more likely to arrive in JSON by default.', 'When two systems need to talk to each other and one only understands XML while the other only produces JSON, a conversion step becomes necessary to bridge them.']],
                ['Tips for working with both formats', ['When converting XML to JSON, watch for attributes on XML tags, since these do not have a direct JSON equivalent and are usually mapped into a special key by the conversion tool.', 'When converting JSON to XML, decide on a consistent tag naming approach for arrays, since JSON arrays do not automatically map to a single obvious XML structure.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['A common mistake is assuming a lossless round-trip conversion. Converting XML to JSON and back to XML does not always reproduce the exact original structure, especially around attributes and comments.', 'Another mistake is choosing a format based on personal preference rather than what the receiving system actually expects, which can create unnecessary conversion steps later.']],
                ['Using conversion tools', ['Use the XML to JSON Converter when integrating an XML-based system with a JSON-based application, and the JSON to XML Converter for the reverse direction.', 'The CSV to JSON Converter is useful when tabular data needs to enter a JSON-based pipeline, which is a common step before working with structured JSON data drawn from spreadsheets.']],
            ], [
                ['Is JSON always better than XML?', 'Not always. JSON is usually more compact and simpler, but XML remains common in certain enterprise and document-based systems.'],
                ['Does XML support data types like JSON does?', 'Not natively. XML represents data as text unless a schema defines specific types.'],
                ['Can I convert XML to JSON without losing information?', 'Mostly, but attributes and some structural details may need special handling to be represented accurately.'],
                ['Which format is more common in modern web APIs?', 'JSON is the more common default for modern REST APIs.'],
                ['Which Toolexa tools help convert between them?', 'Use the XML to JSON Converter and JSON to XML Converter.'],
            ], '2026-07-15'),
            self::article('HTML Formatting Best Practices', 'html-formatting-best-practices', 'HTML Formatting Best Practices', 'Learn practical HTML formatting habits for readable, maintainable markup, including indentation, nesting and entity handling.', 'Developer Tools', 'Clean HTML formatting habits that make markup easier to read, debug and maintain.', ['html-formatter', 'html-entity-encoder-decoder', 'html-to-markdown-converter'], [
                ['Why formatting matters', ['Well-formatted HTML is far easier to scan, debug and hand off to another developer. Poorly indented markup can hide a missing closing tag for a long time, since the browser often renders broken nesting without any visible error.', 'Formatting is not about strict rules for their own sake. Consistent indentation reveals the actual structure of the page, which makes bugs easier to spot before they cause real problems.']],
                ['Step-by-step guide', ['Start by matching indentation to nesting depth. Every time an element opens a new child, indent one level further, and return to the previous level once that child closes.', 'Run compressed or minified HTML through an HTML Formatter before editing it. Reading a single unbroken line of markup is far slower than reading properly indented output.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['A deeply nested navigation menu becomes much easier to review once each list level is indented consistently, revealing exactly which items belong to which submenu.', 'Special characters like ampersands or angle brackets inside visible text need to be encoded as entities rather than typed directly, or they can break the page structure or display incorrectly.']],
                ['Tips for maintainable markup', ['Close tags in the reverse order you opened them, and avoid overlapping tags. Overlapping structures are a frequent source of subtle rendering bugs.', 'Keep semantic tags meaningful. Use heading tags for actual headings and list tags for actual lists, rather than styling plain text to merely look like a heading or list.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['A common mistake is leaving a tag unclosed, which many browsers will silently attempt to fix, hiding a bug that only appears later when a script or style depends on exact structure.', 'Another mistake is typing raw special characters like an ampersand directly into visible text, instead of using the correct HTML entity, which can cause unpredictable rendering in some contexts.']],
                ['Using formatting tools', ['Use HTML Formatter to instantly reindent messy or minified markup for review, and HTML Entity Encoder and Decoder when special characters need to be safely represented inside HTML.', 'When content needs to move into a documentation system, HTML to Markdown Converter can simplify formatted HTML into cleaner Markdown for easier long-term editing.']],
            ], [
                ['Why is HTML indentation important?', 'It reveals element nesting clearly, which makes it easier to spot missing or misplaced closing tags.'],
                ['What are HTML entities used for?', 'They safely represent special characters like ampersands and angle brackets inside HTML content.'],
                ['Does unclosed HTML always cause an error?', 'Not always visibly, since many browsers try to auto-correct it, which can hide bugs until later.'],
                ['Can formatted HTML be converted to Markdown?', 'Yes, use the HTML to Markdown Converter for common content structures.'],
                ['Which tool cleans up messy HTML quickly?', 'Use the HTML Formatter to reindent and structure raw markup.'],
            ], '2026-07-15'),
            self::article('CSS Minification: Why Website Speed Matters', 'css-minification-why-website-speed-matters', 'CSS Minification: Why Website Speed Matters', 'Learn what CSS minification does, how it affects page load speed and how to balance minified and readable stylesheets.', 'Developer Tools', 'Understand how removing whitespace from CSS contributes to faster-loading websites.', ['css-minifier', 'css-beautifier', 'css-gradient-generator'], [
                ['What CSS minification does', ['Minification removes unnecessary whitespace, comments and line breaks from a stylesheet without changing what it does visually, producing a smaller file that downloads and parses faster in the browser.', 'The visual result on the page stays identical. Only the raw file size and readability of the source code change, which is why minification is applied to production files rather than files you actively edit.']],
                ['Step-by-step guide', ['Write and maintain your CSS in a readable, well-formatted state during development, since a minified file is very difficult to edit directly by hand.', 'Before deploying to production, run the readable stylesheet through a CSS Minifier to produce the smaller file that visitors actually download, keeping the original readable version for future edits.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['A stylesheet with generous comments, spacing and indentation might shrink substantially in raw byte size once minified, which directly reduces the amount of data a visitor needs to download before the page can render styled content.', 'On a page with many stylesheets or a slow connection, that reduction in bytes can measurably affect how quickly visible content appears, especially on mobile networks.']],
                ['Tips for a healthy workflow', ['Never edit a minified file directly. Keep a readable source version under version control and treat the minified output as a generated build artifact.', 'If you receive a minified stylesheet and need to understand or modify it, run it through a CSS Beautifier first to restore readable structure before making changes.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['A common mistake is manually editing a minified production file directly, since any typo becomes very hard to spot without formatting, and future automated minification would simply overwrite the manual fix anyway.', 'Another mistake is assuming minification alone solves all speed problems. Excessive unused styles or unnecessarily complex selectors still add weight regardless of whitespace removal.']],
                ['Using CSS tools together', ['Use CSS Minifier for production-ready output, CSS Beautifier when you need to read or edit a compressed stylesheet, and CSS Gradient Generator when building visual effects that you will then minify along with the rest of your styles.', 'Treating formatting and minification as two ends of the same workflow, rather than competing tools, keeps both development speed and production performance in good shape.']],
            ], [
                ['Does minifying CSS change how a page looks?', 'No, minification only removes whitespace and comments; the visual result stays the same.'],
                ['Should I write CSS in minified form directly?', 'No, write readable CSS during development and minify it only for production deployment.'],
                ['How does minification improve page speed?', 'Smaller file sizes download and parse faster, which can improve perceived load time.'],
                ['Can I reverse a minified stylesheet back to readable form?', 'Yes, a CSS Beautifier can restore indentation and line breaks for easier reading.'],
                ['Which Toolexa tool minifies CSS?', 'Use the CSS Minifier tool.'],
            ], '2026-07-15'),
            self::article('Markdown vs HTML for Documentation', 'markdown-vs-html-for-documentation', 'Markdown vs HTML for Documentation', 'Compare Markdown and HTML specifically for technical documentation, README files, wikis and knowledge base articles.', 'Developer Tools', 'A documentation-focused comparison of Markdown and HTML for teams writing technical content.', ['markdown-to-html-converter', 'html-to-markdown-converter', 'html-formatter'], [
                ['Why documentation formats matter', ['Documentation is read far more often than it is written, so the format needs to stay easy to scan, edit and maintain over years, not just look good on the day it was published.', 'Markdown and HTML both appear across documentation systems, but they suit different stages of the documentation lifecycle: Markdown for everyday authoring, HTML for precise embedded structure when needed.']],
                ['Step-by-step guide for documentation teams', ['For README files, internal wikis and most knowledge base articles, default to Markdown. Its plain-text simplicity means anyone on the team can contribute without learning tag syntax.', 'Reach for HTML only inside Markdown when a specific need arises, such as an embedded video, a custom table layout or a collapsible section that plain Markdown cannot express cleanly.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['A getting-started guide with headings, code blocks and bullet lists is comfortably handled by Markdown alone, and stays easy for new contributors to edit in a plain text editor.', 'A documentation page that needs a two-column comparison layout or an embedded interactive widget may need targeted HTML, either written directly or generated from a documentation platform.']],
                ['Tips for documentation teams', ['Keep a consistent heading structure across all documentation pages so both humans and search tools can navigate content predictably.', 'When migrating older HTML-based documentation into a Markdown-based system, convert page by page and manually check for any HTML-specific structure that did not translate cleanly.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['A common mistake is over-using inline HTML inside Markdown files for things Markdown can already do, such as bold text or simple links, which makes the source harder to read for no real benefit.', 'Another mistake is publishing raw, unformatted HTML documentation exports without cleaning up structure, leaving inconsistent indentation that makes future edits error-prone.']],
                ['Using conversion tools for documentation', ['Use Markdown to HTML Converter when a Markdown-based documentation source needs to be published as a styled web page.', 'Use HTML to Markdown Converter when migrating existing HTML documentation into a Markdown-based system, and HTML Formatter to clean up any HTML that remains embedded within documentation pages.']],
            ], [
                ['Should documentation always be written in Markdown?', 'Not always, but Markdown is usually the more practical default for READMEs, wikis and most technical guides.'],
                ['When does documentation need HTML instead?', 'When a page needs embedded media, custom layout or interactive elements that plain Markdown cannot express.'],
                ['Can I mix HTML inside a Markdown file?', 'Yes, most Markdown renderers allow limited inline HTML for specific needs.'],
                ['How do I migrate old HTML docs to Markdown?', 'Convert content page by page with an HTML to Markdown Converter, then manually review structure that did not translate cleanly.'],
                ['Which Toolexa tools help documentation teams?', 'Use Markdown to HTML Converter and HTML to Markdown Converter for format migration.'],
            ], '2026-07-15'),
            self::article('UUID Explained: What It Is and Why Developers Use It', 'uuid-explained-what-it-is-and-why-developers-use-it', 'UUID Explained: What It Is and Why Developers Use It', 'Learn what a UUID is, how it is structured, why developers use it for unique identifiers and how to generate and validate one.', 'Developer Tools', 'A clear explanation of universally unique identifiers and their common uses in software.', ['uuid-generator', 'uuid-validator', 'uuid-batch-generator', 'uuid-decoder-inspector'], [
                ['What is a UUID', ['A UUID, or universally unique identifier, is a long string of characters designed to be unique across systems without requiring a central authority to hand out numbers in sequence.', 'Because the chance of two independently generated UUIDs colliding is extremely small, they are widely trusted as unique keys even when generated by many different machines at the same time.']],
                ['Step-by-step guide', ['When you need a unique identifier for a database record, a session, or a distributed system entity, generate a UUID rather than relying on a simple incrementing number that could collide across systems.', 'Use UUID Generator for a single identifier during development or testing, and UUID Batch Generator when you need many unique identifiers at once, such as for seeding test data.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['A distributed application running on multiple servers can generate UUIDs independently on each server without needing to coordinate with a central counter, since the probability of collision stays negligible.', 'A UUID embedded in a URL or file name avoids revealing sequential information, unlike a simple incrementing ID, which can leak how many records exist in a system.']],
                ['Tips for using UUIDs well', ['Store UUIDs in a consistent format across your system, since some databases store them more efficiently in binary form rather than as plain text strings.', 'Do not assume a UUID is inherently secret or unguessable enough for sensitive access control on its own. Combine it with proper authentication where security actually matters.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['A common mistake is generating UUIDs using a weak or predictable method, which undermines the uniqueness guarantee the format is supposed to provide.', 'Another mistake is validating UUID format visually instead of programmatically, since a string can look roughly UUID-shaped while actually containing invalid characters or an incorrect structure.']],
                ['Using UUID tools', ['Use UUID Generator for single identifiers, UUID Batch Generator for bulk generation, UUID Validator to confirm a given string follows correct UUID format, and UUID Decoder and Inspector to examine the structure and version of an existing UUID.', 'Together, these tools cover the full lifecycle of creating, checking and understanding UUIDs during development.']],
            ], [
                ['What does UUID stand for?', 'UUID stands for universally unique identifier.'],
                ['Can two UUIDs be the same by accident?', 'The probability is extremely small, making collisions practically negligible for most systems.'],
                ['Are UUIDs secure identifiers for authentication?', 'A UUID is not a substitute for proper authentication, though it avoids revealing sequential information.'],
                ['Can I generate multiple UUIDs at once?', 'Yes, use UUID Batch Generator for bulk generation.'],
                ['How can I check if a UUID is valid?', 'Use UUID Validator to confirm correct format and structure.'],
            ], '2026-07-15'),
            self::article('Password Security Best Practices in 2026', 'password-security-best-practices-in-2026', 'Password Security Best Practices in 2026', 'Updated password security practices for 2026, covering passphrase length, password managers, breach checks and multi-factor authentication.', 'Security', 'Modern, practical habits for keeping accounts secure beyond just choosing a strong password.', ['password-generator', 'password-strength-checker', 'random-string-generator'], [
                ['Why password habits keep evolving', ['Password guidance shifts as attackers get faster at guessing and cracking weak credentials, and as more accounts add extra layers like multi-factor authentication alongside the password itself.', 'The direction of modern guidance favors length and uniqueness over complicated symbol requirements, and treats the password as one layer in a broader account security setup rather than the only line of defense.']],
                ['Step-by-step guide for 2026', ['Use a password manager to generate and store a long, random, unique password for every important account, so you never need to memorize or reuse credentials across sites.', 'Enable multi-factor authentication wherever it is offered, especially for email, banking and any account that can be used to reset access to other accounts.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['An email account protected only by a password, even a strong one, remains a single point of failure since email is often used to reset passwords elsewhere. Adding multi-factor authentication closes that gap significantly.', 'A long random passphrase generated and stored in a password manager is generally both easier to use reliably and harder to guess than a shorter password with substituted symbols that a person tries to memorize.']],
                ['Tips for staying secure', ['Check whether your accounts offer passkey or biometric sign-in options where available, since these can reduce reliance on typed passwords for everyday logins.', 'Periodically review which accounts still use old, reused or weak passwords, and prioritize updating the ones tied to financial access, email and identity verification first.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['A common and ongoing mistake is reusing a password across multiple sites, since a breach at one site can expose access to every other account using that same password.', 'Another mistake is treating multi-factor authentication as optional for less important accounts, when in practice it protects both the account and anything else linked to it, such as recovery email addresses.']],
                ['Using password tools responsibly', ['Use Password Generator to create long, random, unique passwords for each account, and Password Strength Checker to understand why a password looks weak or strong before relying on it.', 'Random String Generator can help create secure tokens or keys for development use beyond standard account passwords. Avoid pasting real sensitive credentials into any unfamiliar website.']],
            ], [
                ['Is a longer password always better than a complex one?', 'Length combined with randomness generally matters more than forced symbol complexity for resisting guessing attacks.'],
                ['Should I still use a password manager in 2026?', 'Yes, a password manager remains one of the most practical ways to maintain unique passwords across many accounts.'],
                ['What is the single most impactful extra security step?', 'Enabling multi-factor authentication on important accounts, especially email.'],
                ['Are passkeys replacing passwords entirely?', 'Passkeys are increasingly offered as an option, but many services still support or require passwords, so good password habits remain relevant.'],
                ['Which Toolexa tools help with password security?', 'Use Password Generator and Password Strength Checker for creating and evaluating passwords.'],
            ], '2026-07-15'),
            self::article('QR Code vs Barcode: Complete Comparison', 'qr-code-vs-barcode-complete-comparison', 'QR Code vs Barcode: Complete Comparison', 'A complete side-by-side comparison of QR codes and barcodes across data capacity, scanning, industries and cost to help you decide.', 'Business Tools', 'A decision-focused comparison to help businesses pick the right code type for each use case.', ['qr-generator', 'barcode-generator'], [
                ['Framing the decision', ['Choosing between a QR code and a barcode is less about which technology is newer and more about which one matches the system that will actually scan it and the amount of information it needs to carry.', 'Retail checkout systems, inventory software and customer-facing marketing each tend to favor a different code type, so the right answer often depends on where the code will be used, not personal preference.']],
                ['Comparison by data capacity', ['A barcode typically stores a shorter numeric or alphanumeric identifier, enough for a product lookup code but not much more, since it relies on a simple linear pattern of bars.', 'A QR code uses a two-dimensional grid of modules, allowing it to store significantly more data, including full URLs, text blocks or contact details, within a similarly sized printed area.']],
                ['Comparison by industry use', ['Retail checkout, warehouse inventory and shipping labels have relied on standard barcodes for decades because point-of-sale and inventory systems are built around those specific formats.', 'Marketing materials, restaurant menus, event check-ins and product packaging aimed at consumers increasingly favor QR codes because a phone camera can scan them directly into a link or action.']],
                ['Comparison by scanning requirements', ['Barcodes generally need a dedicated laser or camera scanner aligned closely with the bars, which works well in a controlled checkout environment.', 'QR codes can typically be scanned by any modern smartphone camera from a range of angles and distances, which makes them more practical for public-facing, self-service scanning.']],
                ['Common mistakes when choosing', ['A common mistake is defaulting to whichever code type is more familiar, rather than checking what the destination system, whether a checkout scanner or a customer\'s phone, actually expects.', 'Businesses also sometimes print codes too small for their scanning distance, an error that affects both types but is especially costly at busy checkout counters.']],
                ['Using Toolexa generators', ['Use Barcode Generator when a system requires a standard product identification format like EAN-13, UPC-A or Code128.', 'Use QR Code Generator when the goal is connecting a physical surface to a digital destination, such as a menu, form or product information page, and test the generated code with a real scanner before printing at scale.']],
            ], [
                ['Which stores more data, a QR code or a barcode?', 'A QR code generally stores significantly more data than a traditional linear barcode of similar size.'],
                ['Which is standard for retail checkout?', 'Standard barcodes like EAN or UPC remain the norm for most retail point-of-sale systems.'],
                ['Can a smartphone scan a barcode as easily as a QR code?', 'Many modern phones can scan both, but QR codes are generally designed with flexible camera scanning in mind.'],
                ['Do businesses ever use both on the same product?', 'Yes, it is common to use a barcode for inventory systems and a QR code for customer-facing information on the same packaging.'],
                ['Which Toolexa tools generate these codes?', 'Use Barcode Generator and QR Code Generator depending on your use case.'],
            ], '2026-07-15'),
            self::article('Image Compression Guide Without Losing Quality', 'image-compression-guide-without-losing-quality', 'Image Compression Guide Without Losing Quality', 'A technical walkthrough of format-specific image compression settings for JPG, PNG and WebP to reduce file size while keeping clarity.', 'Image Tools', 'A settings-focused guide to compressing images for online stores, listings and websites.', ['image-compressor', 'image-resizer', 'webp-to-png-converter'], [
                ['Why format choice affects compression results', ['The format you compress in matters as much as the compression setting itself. JPG uses lossy compression well suited to photos, PNG uses lossless compression well suited to sharp edges and transparency, and WebP often achieves a smaller file than either for the same visible quality.', 'Choosing the wrong format before compressing can waste effort, since a photo saved as PNG will usually stay much larger than the same photo saved as a well-compressed JPG or WebP, regardless of the quality setting used.']],
                ['Step-by-step guide for online sellers', ['Start with the source image at its original resolution. Resize it down to the actual display dimensions needed for your listing or website before compressing, since compressing an oversized image wastes quality on detail nobody will see.', 'Apply a moderate compression setting first and inspect the result at real display size, not zoomed in. If product details like fabric texture or text remain clear, the compression level is likely acceptable.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['A product photo intended for an e-commerce listing typically only needs to be as large as the biggest zoom view the platform displays, so compressing after resizing to that dimension avoids unnecessary file weight.', 'A screenshot with sharp text and flat colors compresses very differently from a photograph, and often stays clearer as a PNG or WebP file than as a JPG, where compression artifacts around text edges are more noticeable.']],
                ['Tips for consistent quality across a catalog', ['Apply the same resize dimensions and compression settings across an entire product catalog so listings look visually consistent rather than some images looking noticeably softer than others.', 'Keep the original uncompressed images archived separately, since re-compressing an already-compressed image repeatedly tends to degrade quality further each time.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['A common mistake among online sellers is uploading full camera-resolution images directly without resizing first, which slows down page loading without adding any visible benefit to the customer.', 'Another mistake is applying the heaviest compression setting to every image uniformly, without checking that fine details, like small printed text on packaging, remain legible at the final compressed size.']],
                ['Using Toolexa image tools', ['Use Image Resizer first to bring dimensions down to what is actually needed, then Image Compressor to reduce file size at that corrected dimension.', 'Use WebP to PNG Converter when a platform requires PNG specifically but your source image was optimized in WebP format.']],
            ], [
                ['Which format compresses best for photos?', 'JPG or WebP generally compress photos more efficiently than PNG for similar visible quality.'],
                ['Should I resize before or after compressing?', 'Resize first, then compress, since compressing an oversized image wastes effort on detail that will not be visible at the final display size.'],
                ['Does repeated compression degrade quality further?', 'Yes, compressing an already lossy-compressed image again can degrade quality more than compressing the original once.'],
                ['Is WebP better than JPG for e-commerce?', 'WebP often produces a smaller file at similar visible quality, though platform support should be checked first.'],
                ['Which Toolexa tools help sellers compress product photos?', 'Use Image Resizer and Image Compressor together for the best balance of size and quality.'],
            ], '2026-07-15'),
            self::article('Image Formats Explained: JPG, PNG, WebP, SVG & GIF', 'image-formats-explained-jpg-png-webp-svg-gif', 'Image Formats Explained: JPG, PNG, WebP, SVG and GIF', 'Understand the differences between JPG, PNG, WebP, SVG and GIF formats and when to use each one for web and design work.', 'Image Tools', 'A practical guide to choosing the right image format for photos, graphics, icons and animations.', ['jpg-to-png-converter', 'png-to-jpg-converter', 'webp-to-png-converter', 'png-to-svg-converter'], [
                ['Overview of common formats', ['JPG is a lossy format best suited to photographs with smooth color gradients. PNG is a lossless format best suited to graphics with sharp edges, text or transparency. WebP is a newer format that can behave like either, often at a smaller file size.', 'SVG is a vector format built from mathematical shapes rather than pixels, making it ideal for logos and icons that need to scale to any size without losing sharpness. GIF is an older format mainly used today for simple looping animations.']],
                ['Step-by-step guide for choosing a format', ['Ask what the image actually contains. A photo favors JPG or WebP. A logo or icon favors SVG. A screenshot with transparency favors PNG or WebP. A short looping animation favors GIF or a modern animated format where supported.', 'If you are unsure, start with the source format you have and convert it using the appropriate converter once you know the destination requirement, such as a platform that only accepts PNG uploads.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['A company logo used across a website header, favicon and printed material benefits from being stored as SVG, since it can be resized to any dimension without becoming blurry or pixelated.', 'A product photo gallery on an online store is usually better served by JPG or WebP, since photographic detail compresses efficiently in those formats compared with PNG.']],
                ['Tips for choosing wisely', ['Keep a master version of important graphics in a lossless or vector format, and export compressed versions like JPG or WebP only for the final delivered use case, such as a web page.', 'Check platform requirements before uploading. Some systems only accept specific formats, which is where format converters become genuinely useful rather than optional.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['A common mistake is using PNG for large photographs, resulting in unnecessarily large file sizes compared with a well-compressed JPG or WebP of the same image.', 'Another mistake is exporting a logo as a JPG, which forces a solid background and can introduce compression artifacts around otherwise crisp edges that a vector or PNG format would preserve.']],
                ['Using Toolexa format converters', ['Use JPG to PNG Converter and PNG to JPG Converter when a platform requires a specific format that differs from your source file.', 'Use WebP to PNG Converter when you need broader compatibility with tools that do not support WebP, and PNG to SVG Converter when converting simple flat graphics toward a scalable vector format.']],
            ], [
                ['Which format is best for photos?', 'JPG or WebP are generally best for photographic images due to efficient lossy compression.'],
                ['Which format is best for logos and icons?', 'SVG is usually best since it scales to any size without losing sharpness.'],
                ['When should I use PNG instead of JPG?', 'Use PNG when you need transparency or sharp edges, such as screenshots or graphics with text.'],
                ['Is GIF still relevant today?', 'GIF is still used mainly for short, simple looping animations, though other formats can offer better quality at smaller sizes.'],
                ['Which Toolexa tools help convert between formats?', 'Use JPG to PNG Converter, PNG to JPG Converter, WebP to PNG Converter and PNG to SVG Converter depending on your need.'],
            ], '2026-07-15'),
            self::article('PDF Merge vs PDF Split: Which Tool Do You Need?', 'pdf-merge-vs-pdf-split-which-tool-do-you-need', 'PDF Merge vs PDF Split: Which Tool Do You Need?', 'Learn when to merge PDFs together and when to split a PDF into separate files, with practical scenarios for each.', 'PDF Tools', 'A quick decision guide for choosing between combining and separating PDF documents.', ['pdf-merger', 'pdf-splitter', 'pdf-page-counter'], [
                ['Understanding the two tasks', ['Merging combines multiple separate PDF files into a single document, useful when you need one file instead of several attachments. Splitting does the opposite, breaking one PDF into smaller separate files, useful when only part of a document needs to be shared.', 'The two tasks solve opposite problems, but people sometimes reach for the wrong one simply because they are unsure which direction their situation actually requires.']],
                ['Step-by-step guide', ['If you have several separate documents that need to travel together, such as a resume, cover letter and certificate, merge them into one PDF before submitting.', 'If you have one large PDF but only need to share a specific section, such as a single chapter or a signed page, split the document first rather than sending the entire file.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['A job applicant combining a resume, portfolio and reference letter into a single upload should use a PDF merger, since most application portals expect one file per document type.', 'Someone who scanned a multi-page contract but only needs to share the signature page separately should use a PDF splitter to extract that one page without altering the original file.']],
                ['Tips for a clean result', ['Before merging, check the page order needed in the final document and arrange the source files accordingly, since most merge tools combine files in the order they are added.', 'Before splitting, use PDF Page Counter to confirm the exact page numbers you need to extract, since guessing page ranges in a long document often leads to a mismatch.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['A common mistake is merging files in the wrong order and only noticing after the document has already been submitted or shared.', 'Another mistake is splitting a document into individual pages when only a specific range was actually needed, creating more files than necessary to manage.']],
                ['Using the right PDF tool', ['Use PDF Merger when multiple files need to become one, and PDF Splitter when one file needs to become several focused pieces.', 'Use PDF Page Counter alongside either tool to confirm page counts and ordering before finalizing the merge or split.']],
            ], [
                ['When should I merge PDFs instead of splitting?', 'Merge when you have multiple separate documents that need to be submitted or shared as a single file.'],
                ['Can I extract just one page from a PDF?', 'Yes, use PDF Splitter to extract a specific page or range from a larger document.'],
                ['Does merging change the page order of source files?', 'The pages typically follow the order the source files are arranged in before merging, so check the order first.'],
                ['How do I know how many pages to extract when splitting?', 'Use PDF Page Counter first to confirm exact page numbers before splitting.'],
                ['Which Toolexa tools handle these tasks?', 'Use PDF Merger to combine files and PDF Splitter to separate them.'],
            ], '2026-07-15'),
            self::article('PDF Security: Password Protection Explained', 'pdf-security-password-protection-explained', 'PDF Security: Password Protection Explained', 'Understand how PDF password protection works, how to check if a PDF is protected and best practices for sharing sensitive documents.', 'PDF Tools', 'A practical look at how PDF password protection keeps sensitive documents safer when sharing.', ['pdf-password-checker', 'pdf-metadata-viewer', 'pdf-merger'], [
                ['How PDF password protection works', ['A password-protected PDF requires a password before it can be opened or, in some cases, before certain actions like printing or editing are allowed, depending on the type of restriction applied.', 'This protection is applied when the file is created or exported, and it stays in effect until someone with the correct password removes it, making it a useful layer for sharing sensitive documents.']],
                ['Step-by-step guide', ['Before sharing a sensitive PDF such as a financial statement or personal document, decide whether it needs to be opening-restricted, so only someone with the password can view it at all.', 'If you receive a PDF and are unsure whether it is protected before attempting to open it in an unfamiliar tool, use PDF Password Checker to confirm its protection status first.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['A business sharing an invoice containing sensitive account details might password-protect the file before emailing it, and share the password separately through a different channel for added safety.', 'Someone receiving a bank statement or tax document as a PDF often finds it password-protected with a hint such as a specific personal identifier to open it, a common practice for automated document delivery.']],
                ['Tips for safer sharing', ['Share the document and its password through separate communication channels, such as email for the file and a text message for the password, so intercepting one does not expose the other.', 'Check what a PDF file reveals through PDF Metadata Viewer before sharing externally, since metadata can sometimes include an author name or editing history you did not intend to disclose.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['A common mistake is sending the password in the same email as the protected file, which defeats much of the purpose of separating the two for security.', 'Another mistake is assuming password protection alone guarantees strong security. A weak, guessable password undermines the protection just as a weak account password would.']],
                ['Using PDF security tools responsibly', ['Use PDF Password Checker to confirm whether a file is protected before attempting to open it elsewhere, and PDF Metadata Viewer to review what information a document exposes before sharing.', 'PDF Merger can help combine multiple protected sections into a single organized document, though each source file\'s protection status should be checked beforehand.']],
            ], [
                ['What does a password-protected PDF prevent?', 'It typically prevents opening the file, and sometimes printing or editing, without the correct password.'],
                ['Can I check if a PDF is password-protected without opening it in unfamiliar software?', 'Yes, use PDF Password Checker to confirm its protection status safely.'],
                ['Is it safe to send the password in the same email as the file?', 'No, it is safer to share the password through a separate communication channel.'],
                ['Does PDF metadata reveal sensitive information?', 'It can sometimes include details like author name or editing history, so check it with PDF Metadata Viewer before sharing.'],
                ['Which Toolexa tool checks PDF password status?', 'Use PDF Password Checker.'],
            ], '2026-07-15'),
            self::article('Color Codes Explained: HEX, RGB, HSL and CMYK', 'color-codes-explained-hex-rgb-hsl-cmyk', 'Color Codes Explained: HEX, RGB, HSL and CMYK', 'Understand HEX, RGB, HSL and CMYK color formats, including why print design uses CMYK while screens use RGB-based formats.', 'Color Tools', 'A format-by-format guide to the color codes used across web design and print.', ['hex-rgb-hsl-color-converter', 'color-picker-from-image', 'css-gradient-generator'], [
                ['Screen formats versus print formats', ['HEX, RGB and HSL all describe color the way a screen produces it, by combining light from red, green and blue elements. CMYK describes color the way a printer produces it, by combining cyan, magenta, yellow and black ink on paper.', 'This distinction matters because a color that looks vivid on a screen using RGB-based values can look noticeably different once printed, since ink and light mix colors in fundamentally different ways.']],
                ['Step-by-step guide', ['For web and app design, work in HEX, RGB or HSL, since these directly map to how a browser or design tool renders color on screen.', 'For anything destined for print, such as packaging or business cards, convert design colors to CMYK values, or at minimum preview a CMYK approximation before finalizing, since the final printed result depends on ink mixing rather than light.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['A bright screen blue defined in HEX may appear noticeably duller once printed in CMYK, because the ink-based gamut cannot reproduce certain vivid screen colors exactly.', 'A brand color used consistently across a website, a printed brochure and a physical product label needs both a screen-based value like HEX and a print-ready CMYK equivalent to stay visually consistent across mediums.']],
                ['Tips for consistent branding', ['Document brand colors in more than one format from the start: HEX or RGB for digital use, and CMYK for print use, so designers do not have to guess or approximate later.', 'When a color must match exactly across screen and print, expect small unavoidable differences and choose the closest practical CMYK equivalent rather than assuming an identical result.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['A common mistake is sending a HEX or RGB color directly to a print vendor without a CMYK conversion, resulting in printed colors that look different from what was designed on screen.', 'Another mistake is assuming HSL, which is convenient for adjusting lightness and saturation during design, has any direct meaning in a print context, where CMYK ink percentages are what actually matter.']],
                ['Using color tools', ['Use the HEX RGB HSL Color Converter for screen-based design work, and Color Picker From Image to sample colors directly from photos or existing artwork.', 'CSS Gradient Generator is useful for building smooth web-based color transitions using HEX or RGB values once your screen-based palette is finalized.']],
            ], [
                ['Why does a screen color look different when printed?', 'Screens use light-based RGB color while printers use ink-based CMYK color, and the two do not produce identical results for every color.'],
                ['Should I design in CMYK from the start?', 'For print-focused work, previewing in CMYK helps avoid surprises, though most design tools still work primarily in RGB or HEX.'],
                ['What is HSL best used for?', 'HSL is useful for adjusting a color\'s lightness or saturation intuitively during screen-based design.'],
                ['Can I convert HEX to other color formats easily?', 'Yes, use the HEX RGB HSL Color Converter to move between screen-based formats.'],
                ['Which tool helps sample colors from an existing image?', 'Use Color Picker From Image.'],
            ], '2026-07-15'),
            self::article('How to Choose the Right Color Palette', 'how-to-choose-the-right-color-palette', 'How to Choose the Right Color Palette', 'Learn how to build a cohesive color palette for websites and brands using contrast, harmony and accessibility principles.', 'Color Tools', 'A practical approach to picking colors that work well together and stay readable.', ['color-palette-generator', 'hex-rgb-hsl-color-converter', 'color-picker-from-image'], [
                ['What makes a palette work', ['A good color palette is not just a set of colors someone likes individually. It is a small group of colors that work together consistently across buttons, text, backgrounds and accents without competing for attention.', 'Most workable palettes include a dominant color, one or two supporting colors, and a neutral tone for text and backgrounds, rather than many equally loud colors fighting for focus.']],
                ['Step-by-step guide', ['Start with one anchor color, often tied to brand identity or the primary mood you want to convey. Build supporting colors around it using a harmony approach such as complementary or analogous relationships.', 'Use Color Palette Generator to explore variations around your anchor color, then test the resulting palette on real layout elements like buttons and headings rather than judging swatches alone.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['A palette built around a deep blue anchor might use a warm accent color sparingly for calls to action, with light and dark neutral tones handling most of the background and text.', 'A palette pulled directly from a product photo using Color Picker From Image can create a natural, cohesive feel between marketing visuals and the surrounding page design.']],
                ['Tips for accessible palettes', ['Always check contrast between text color and background color. A visually appealing palette can still fail basic readability if contrast is too low.', 'Limit how many colors carry meaning, such as red for errors or green for success. Overloading color meaning across a palette makes the interface harder to interpret quickly.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['A common mistake is choosing colors purely by personal taste without testing them together on actual buttons, text and backgrounds, where interactions between colors become obvious.', 'Another mistake is using too many saturated colors at once, which can make a design feel chaotic instead of intentional, even when each individual color looks fine alone.']],
                ['Using color tools together', ['Use Color Palette Generator to explore harmonious combinations, HEX RGB HSL Color Converter to fine-tune a specific shade across formats, and Color Picker From Image when you want a palette inspired by an existing photo or artwork.', 'Testing the finished palette across real design elements, not just swatches, is the step that separates a good palette from a great one.']],
            ], [
                ['How many colors should a palette have?', 'Most effective palettes use a small set: one dominant color, one or two supporting colors and a couple of neutrals.'],
                ['Why does contrast matter in a color palette?', 'Low contrast between text and background can make content hard to read, regardless of how attractive the colors look together.'],
                ['Can I build a palette from a photo?', 'Yes, use Color Picker From Image to sample colors directly from an existing image.'],
                ['What is a harmony-based approach to color?', 'It means choosing supporting colors based on their relationship to an anchor color, such as complementary or analogous positions on the color wheel.'],
                ['Which Toolexa tool generates palettes automatically?', 'Use Color Palette Generator.'],
            ], '2026-07-15'),
            self::article('Understanding SHA-256 Hashing', 'understanding-sha-256-hashing', 'Understanding SHA-256 Hashing', 'Learn what SHA-256 hashing is, how it differs from encryption, common use cases and how to generate a hash for file or text verification.', 'Security', 'A beginner-friendly explanation of SHA-256 and how developers use it for integrity checks.', ['sha-256-hash-generator', 'md5-hash-generator', 'password-strength-checker'], [
                ['What SHA-256 does', ['SHA-256 takes any input, whether a short word or a large file, and produces a fixed-length string of characters called a hash. The same input always produces the same hash, but even a tiny change in the input produces a completely different hash.', 'This property makes SHA-256 useful for verifying that a file or piece of text has not been altered, since comparing hashes is far faster than comparing entire files byte by byte.']],
                ['Step-by-step guide', ['To verify a file has not been tampered with, generate its SHA-256 hash and compare it against a hash published by the original source. If the hashes match exactly, the file content is identical.', 'Use SHA-256 Hash Generator to produce a hash from text or file content, then compare the result character by character against the expected value.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['Software downloads are often published alongside a SHA-256 hash so users can confirm the downloaded file matches exactly what the publisher released, catching corruption or tampering during transfer.', 'Developers sometimes use SHA-256 hashes as unique fingerprints for data deduplication, comparing hashes instead of comparing large data blocks directly to check for duplicates.']],
                ['Tips for using hashes correctly', ['Always compare the full hash string exactly. Even one differing character means the inputs are not identical, regardless of how similar the rest of the hash looks.', 'Remember that SHA-256 is one-way. You cannot reverse a hash back into the original input, which is exactly why it works well for verification rather than storage of retrievable data.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['A common mistake is confusing hashing with encryption. Hashing is one-way and not meant to be reversed, while encryption is designed to be decrypted with the correct key.', 'Another mistake is relying on older, weaker hash algorithms like MD5 for security-sensitive verification, when SHA-256 offers stronger collision resistance for that purpose.']],
                ['Using hashing tools', ['Use SHA-256 Hash Generator for security-relevant verification tasks, and MD5 Hash Generator only for lightweight, non-security checksum purposes where legacy compatibility is required.', 'Password Strength Checker is a separate but related tool, useful for understanding password quality rather than hashing itself.']],
            ], [
                ['Is SHA-256 the same as encryption?', 'No, hashing is one-way and cannot be reversed, while encryption is designed to be decrypted with a key.'],
                ['Why do software downloads publish a SHA-256 hash?', 'So users can verify the downloaded file matches the original exactly and has not been corrupted or tampered with.'],
                ['Can two different inputs produce the same SHA-256 hash?', 'It is designed to make this extremely unlikely, which is what makes it useful for verification.'],
                ['Is MD5 as secure as SHA-256?', 'No, MD5 is considered weaker and less suitable for security-sensitive verification compared with SHA-256.'],
                ['Which Toolexa tool generates a SHA-256 hash?', 'Use SHA-256 Hash Generator.'],
            ], '2026-07-15'),
            self::article('Robots.txt Explained for Beginners', 'robots-txt-explained-for-beginners', 'Robots.txt Explained for Beginners', 'Learn what a robots.txt file does, how search engines use it and how to create a basic robots.txt file for your website.', 'SEO Tools', 'A beginner-friendly explanation of how robots.txt guides search engine crawlers.', ['robots-txt-generator', 'xml-sitemap-generator', 'keyword-density-checker'], [
                ['What robots.txt does', ['A robots.txt file sits at the root of a website and gives search engine crawlers general instructions about which parts of the site they are welcome to crawl and which parts they should avoid.', 'It is a set of guidelines rather than a strict security barrier. Well-behaved crawlers generally respect it, but it does not prevent a page from being accessed directly if someone has the link.']],
                ['Step-by-step guide', ['Identify which sections of your site do not need to be crawled, such as internal search result pages or admin areas, and which sections, like your main content, should remain fully crawlable.', 'Use Robots.txt Generator to build a correctly formatted file with the right directives, then place it at the root of your domain so crawlers can find it automatically.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['A website might disallow crawling of a checkout or account page that offers no value in search results, while explicitly allowing crawling of blog and product pages that should appear in search.', 'Many robots.txt files also reference the location of the site\'s XML sitemap, helping crawlers discover the full list of pages worth indexing more efficiently.']],
                ['Tips for a healthy robots.txt', ['Avoid blocking entire important sections of your site by mistake. A single overly broad rule can accidentally hide valuable content from search engines.', 'Review robots.txt whenever you restructure your website, since old rules referencing pages that no longer exist, or missing rules for new sections, can quietly cause crawling issues.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['A common mistake is blocking a page in robots.txt while still expecting it to appear in search results, since blocking crawling can prevent a page from being properly indexed or understood.', 'Another mistake is treating robots.txt as a security tool. Sensitive content should be protected with proper access control, not just hidden from crawlers through robots.txt.']],
                ['Using SEO tools together', ['Use Robots.txt Generator to create the file itself, and XML Sitemap Generator to build the sitemap that robots.txt often references.', 'Keyword Density Checker is a separate on-page SEO tool, useful once crawlable pages are set up correctly and you are refining page content itself.']],
            ], [
                ['What is robots.txt used for?', 'It gives search engine crawlers general guidance on which parts of a website to crawl or avoid.'],
                ['Does robots.txt guarantee a page will not be seen?', 'No, it discourages crawling by well-behaved bots but does not prevent direct access to a page link.'],
                ['Can robots.txt block a page from appearing in search results?', 'Blocking crawling can affect indexing, but it is not the recommended way to keep sensitive pages private.'],
                ['Should robots.txt reference my sitemap?', 'Yes, many robots.txt files include a reference to help crawlers discover the sitemap.'],
                ['Which Toolexa tool creates a robots.txt file?', 'Use Robots.txt Generator.'],
            ], '2026-07-15'),
            self::article('XML Sitemap Guide for Better SEO', 'xml-sitemap-guide-for-better-seo', 'XML Sitemap Guide for Better SEO', 'Learn what an XML sitemap does, how it helps search engines discover pages and how to create and maintain one properly.', 'SEO Tools', 'A practical guide to building and maintaining an XML sitemap for search visibility.', ['xml-sitemap-generator', 'robots-txt-generator', 'open-graph-meta-tag-generator'], [
                ['What an XML sitemap does', ['An XML sitemap is a structured list of a website\'s pages, submitted to search engines to help them discover content more efficiently, especially on larger sites or sites with pages that are not easily reached through internal links alone.', 'It does not guarantee ranking or even indexing, but it improves the odds that search engines find and consider your important pages in a timely way.']],
                ['Step-by-step guide', ['List the pages that matter for search visibility: main content pages, category pages and key landing pages. Exclude pages that offer no search value, such as internal utility pages.', 'Use XML Sitemap Generator to build a correctly formatted sitemap file, then submit it through your search engine\'s webmaster tools and reference it from your robots.txt file.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['A blog that regularly publishes new articles benefits from an updated sitemap, since it helps search engines discover new content faster than waiting for organic link discovery alone.', 'An online store with many product pages can use a sitemap to ensure new or updated products are surfaced to crawlers promptly, especially before internal links from category pages have propagated.']],
                ['Tips for maintaining a sitemap', ['Keep the sitemap updated as pages are added or removed. A sitemap listing pages that no longer exist can waste crawl attention and create confusing signals.', 'For very large sites, consider splitting content into multiple sitemap files referenced from a sitemap index, since a single sitemap file has practical size and entry limits.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['A common mistake is including pages that should not be indexed, such as duplicate or low-value pages, which dilutes the sitemap\'s usefulness as a clear signal of important content.', 'Another mistake is generating a sitemap once and never updating it again, letting it drift out of sync with the site\'s actual current structure.']],
                ['Using SEO tools together', ['Use XML Sitemap Generator to build the sitemap file itself, Robots.txt Generator to reference it correctly, and Open Graph Meta Tag Generator to make sure the pages listed in your sitemap also present well when shared on social platforms.', 'Together, these tools support both search engine discovery and social sharing quality.']],
            ], [
                ['Does an XML sitemap guarantee my pages will rank?', 'No, it helps with discovery and indexing, but ranking depends on many other factors.'],
                ['Should every page be included in the sitemap?', 'No, include pages that provide search value and exclude low-value or duplicate pages.'],
                ['How often should I update my sitemap?', 'Update it whenever pages are added, removed or significantly changed.'],
                ['What happens for very large websites?', 'Large sites often use multiple sitemap files referenced from a sitemap index due to size limits.'],
                ['Which Toolexa tool builds a sitemap?', 'Use XML Sitemap Generator.'],
            ], '2026-07-15'),
            self::article('Keyword Density: SEO Myths vs Reality', 'keyword-density-seo-myths-vs-reality', 'Keyword Density: SEO Myths vs Reality', 'Separate keyword density myths from reality, understand what search engines actually value and how to check keyword usage sensibly.', 'SEO Tools', 'A clear-eyed look at keyword density and why obsessing over an exact percentage misses the point.', ['keyword-density-checker', 'word-counter', 'character-counter'], [
                ['Where the keyword density myth comes from', ['Keyword density is the percentage of times a specific word or phrase appears relative to the total word count of a page. Some older SEO advice treated a specific target percentage as a ranking requirement, which is largely outdated thinking today.', 'Modern search engines evaluate content quality, relevance and user experience far more broadly than counting exact keyword repetitions, making an obsessive focus on hitting a precise density number counterproductive.']],
                ['What actually matters instead', ['Search engines generally reward content that naturally and clearly covers a topic, using related terms and variations rather than repeating one exact phrase mechanically throughout a page.', 'Readability and genuine usefulness to a real reader tend to correlate with better search performance far more reliably than any specific keyword repetition count.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['A well-written article about a topic will naturally include the main keyword a reasonable number of times simply through normal writing, without needing to force extra repetitions to hit an arbitrary target.', 'Stuffing a keyword unnaturally into a sentence, to the point where it reads awkwardly to a human, is far more likely to hurt trust and readability than to help search visibility.']],
                ['Tips for sensible keyword usage', ['Write for the reader first, then check afterward whether your main topic and related terms appear naturally throughout the content, rather than writing toward a density target from the start.', 'Use keyword variations and related phrases rather than repeating one exact phrase repeatedly, since this tends to read more naturally and can cover a broader range of related searches.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['A common mistake is chasing a specific density percentage as if it were a hard ranking rule, which can lead to awkward, repetitive writing that reads poorly to actual visitors.', 'Another mistake is ignoring keyword usage entirely and never checking whether a page actually addresses its intended topic clearly, swinging too far in the opposite direction.']],
                ['Using keyword tools sensibly', ['Use Keyword Density Checker as a diagnostic check after writing, not as a target to write toward, to spot pages that are either keyword-thin or unnaturally repetitive.', 'Word Counter and Character Counter are useful companions for checking overall content length and structure, which also plays a role in how thoroughly a topic is covered.']],
            ], [
                ['Does hitting an exact keyword density percentage guarantee better rankings?', 'No, modern search engines evaluate overall content quality and relevance far more broadly than a single density number.'],
                ['Is keyword density completely irrelevant then?', 'It is not irrelevant as a diagnostic check, but it should not be the primary writing goal.'],
                ['What should I focus on instead of density?', 'Focus on covering the topic clearly and naturally, using related terms and genuinely useful content.'],
                ['Can keyword stuffing hurt my page?', 'Yes, unnatural repetition can hurt readability and trust, which can indirectly hurt performance.'],
                ['Which Toolexa tool checks keyword density?', 'Use Keyword Density Checker as a post-writing diagnostic tool.'],
            ], '2026-07-15'),
            self::article('Open Graph Tags Explained for Social Media', 'open-graph-tags-explained-for-social-media', 'Open Graph Tags Explained for Social Media', 'Learn what Open Graph tags do, how they control link previews on social platforms and how to set them up correctly.', 'SEO Tools', 'A practical guide to controlling how your links look when shared on social media.', ['open-graph-meta-tag-generator', 'url-slug-generator', 'xml-sitemap-generator'], [
                ['What Open Graph tags do', ['Open Graph tags are meta tags placed in a page\'s HTML that tell social platforms what title, description and image to show when that page\'s link is shared, instead of leaving the platform to guess.', 'Without these tags, a shared link may display an inconsistent or unappealing preview, pulling the wrong image or an awkward snippet of text instead of a deliberately chosen preview.']],
                ['Step-by-step guide', ['Decide on a clear title, a concise description and a representative image for each important page you expect people to share, similar to how you would write a search snippet.', 'Use Open Graph Meta Tag Generator to produce the correct tag markup, then add it to the page\'s HTML head section so social platforms can read it when the link is shared.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['A blog article shared on social media with a clear Open Graph title and an eye-catching image is generally more likely to earn clicks than a bare link with an auto-generated, mismatched preview.', 'An e-commerce product page with a correctly set Open Graph image showing the actual product creates a more trustworthy, recognizable preview when a customer shares the link with a friend.']],
                ['Tips for effective previews', ['Keep the Open Graph title and description distinct from your page\'s search meta tags if needed, since social sharing context can call for a slightly different tone than a search result snippet.', 'Choose an image with the right dimensions and aspect ratio recommended for social platforms, so it displays cleanly rather than being awkwardly cropped in the preview.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['A common mistake is leaving Open Graph tags missing entirely, letting platforms guess at a preview instead of controlling it deliberately.', 'Another mistake is using a generic site-wide image for every page\'s Open Graph tag, missing the opportunity to show a specific, relevant image for each individual piece of content.']],
                ['Using SEO tools together', ['Use Open Graph Meta Tag Generator to build correct tag markup, URL Slug Generator to keep the shared link itself clean and readable, and XML Sitemap Generator to ensure the same pages are properly discoverable by search engines as well as shareable on social platforms.', 'Treating search visibility and social sharing as connected, rather than separate concerns, produces more consistent results across channels.']],
            ], [
                ['What are Open Graph tags used for?', 'They control the title, description and image shown when a page link is shared on social platforms.'],
                ['What happens if a page has no Open Graph tags?', 'The platform may generate an inconsistent or unappealing preview automatically.'],
                ['Should the Open Graph description match my meta description?', 'It can be similar, but it may be tailored differently since social sharing context can differ from search context.'],
                ['Does image size matter for Open Graph tags?', 'Yes, using recommended dimensions helps the image display cleanly instead of being awkwardly cropped.'],
                ['Which Toolexa tool generates Open Graph tags?', 'Use Open Graph Meta Tag Generator.'],
            ], '2026-07-15'),
            self::article('URL Slugs: Best SEO Practices', 'url-slugs-best-seo-practices', 'URL Slugs: Best SEO Practices', 'Learn how to write clean, SEO-friendly URL slugs, including length, keyword placement and formatting best practices.', 'SEO Tools', 'A practical guide to writing URL slugs that are clear for readers and friendly for search engines.', ['url-slug-generator', 'url-encoder-decoder', 'url-parser'], [
                ['What makes a good URL slug', ['A URL slug is the readable part of a web address that identifies a specific page, and a good one is short, descriptive and easy for a human to understand at a glance before even clicking.', 'Search engines and readers both benefit from clear slugs. A descriptive slug gives a quick hint about page content, while a vague or overly long one adds friction without offering any real benefit.']],
                ['Step-by-step guide', ['Start from your page title and trim it down to the essential words that describe the content, removing filler words that do not add clarity.', 'Use URL Slug Generator to convert a title into a clean, lowercase, hyphen-separated slug automatically, avoiding manual formatting mistakes like inconsistent capitalization or stray spaces.']],
                ['Practical examples', ['A page about comparing two products is better served by a slug that names both products clearly than by a generic slug that gives no hint about the actual comparison.', 'A long, keyword-stuffed slug that repeats the same term multiple times is usually less effective than a shorter, natural slug that still contains the core topic once.']],
                ['Tips for writing slugs', ['Use hyphens to separate words rather than underscores or spaces, since hyphens are the widely accepted standard that search engines parse most reliably.', 'Keep slugs stable once published. Changing a slug after a page has been indexed and shared can break existing links unless a proper redirect is set up.']],
                ['Common mistakes', ['A common mistake is including unnecessary words, numbers or dates in a slug that add length without adding clarity, especially for evergreen content that should not look dated.', 'Another mistake is using special characters or spaces directly in a URL, which browsers and servers must encode awkwardly, making the link harder to read and share.']],
                ['Using URL tools together', ['Use URL Slug Generator to create clean slugs from titles, URL Encoder and Decoder when a URL needs special characters safely represented, and URL Parser to break down an existing URL into its components for review or debugging.', 'Together, these tools help keep URLs clean both for search engines and for people copying and sharing links.']],
            ], [
                ['What is a URL slug?', 'It is the readable part of a web address that identifies a specific page.'],
                ['Should I use hyphens or underscores in a slug?', 'Hyphens are the widely recommended standard for separating words in a URL slug.'],
                ['Can I change a slug after publishing?', 'You can, but it may break existing links unless a redirect is set up from the old URL to the new one.'],
                ['Should a slug include the exact keyword?', 'Including the core topic naturally is helpful, but avoid stuffing the same keyword multiple times.'],
                ['Which Toolexa tool creates clean slugs?', 'Use URL Slug Generator.'],
            ], '2026-07-15'),
        ];
    }

    private static function article(string $title, string $slug, string $metaTitle, string $metaDescription, string $category, string $excerpt, array $relatedTools, array $sections, array $faqs, string $publishedAt = '2026-07-06'): array
    {
        return [
            'title' => $title,
            'slug' => $slug,
            'meta_title' => $metaTitle,
            'meta_description' => $metaDescription,
            'category' => $category,
            'excerpt' => $excerpt,
            'author' => 'Toolexa Editorial Team',
            'published_at' => $publishedAt,
            'featured_image' => null,
            'related_tools' => $relatedTools,
            'sections' => array_merge(
                collect($sections)->map(fn (array $section) => [
                    'heading' => $section[0],
                    'paragraphs' => $section[1],
                ])->all(),
                self::supportingSections($title, $category, $relatedTools)
            ),
            'faqs' => collect($faqs)->map(fn (array $faq) => [
                'question' => $faq[0],
                'answer' => $faq[1],
            ])->all(),
        ];
    }

    private static function supportingSections(string $title, string $category, array $relatedTools): array
    {
        $toolText = collect($relatedTools)
            ->map(fn (string $slug) => Str::headline(str_replace('-', ' ', $slug)))
            ->join(', ', ' and ');

        return [
            ['heading' => 'A practical workflow you can follow', 'paragraphs' => [
                'Start with the real question you want to answer, not with the tool itself. For '.$title.', write down the input values, the expected output and the decision you need to make after seeing the result. This keeps the work focused and prevents unnecessary trial and error.',
                'Next, enter one complete example in the relevant Toolexa tool and review the result before changing anything. If the output looks sensible, adjust one value at a time. This habit is useful for '.$category.' topics because it shows which input has the biggest effect on the final answer.',
            ]],
            ['heading' => 'How to check your inputs before trusting the result', 'paragraphs' => [
                'Most mistakes happen before the calculation, conversion or generation starts. A misplaced zero, wrong unit, incorrect rate, unsupported format or copied space can change the result completely. Before using the output, quickly compare every field with the original source you are working from.',
                'For important work, run the same example twice: once with exact values and once with rounded values. If the difference is large, use the exact version. If the difference is tiny, rounded values may be good enough for planning, drafts or quick comparisons.',
            ]],
            ['heading' => 'Practical examples you can test yourself', 'paragraphs' => [
                'Create three test cases: a small value, a normal real-life value and an unusually large value. The small value helps you understand the behavior, the normal value reflects your actual task, and the large value shows whether the result still makes sense at scale.',
                'If one test case produces a surprising result, do not ignore it. Recheck the input, read the label beside the field and compare the output with a simpler example. Surprising results often reveal a wrong assumption rather than a broken tool.',
            ]],
            ['heading' => 'Tips for better results', 'paragraphs' => [
                'Keep source information close while using the tool. On mobile, copy values carefully before switching tabs. On desktop, open related Toolexa tools in separate tabs when you need to compare several scenarios or output formats.',
                'Use copy and download buttons where available instead of manually selecting text. This reduces accidental missing characters, extra spaces and formatting mistakes, especially for codes, dates, JSON, color values and financial summaries.',
            ]],
            ['heading' => 'Common mistakes to avoid', 'paragraphs' => [
                'Do not rely on a result without checking the input type, unit, format or assumption behind it. Most wrong outputs come from entering the right number in the wrong field or using a setting that does not match the real task.',
                'Another common mistake is treating a quick result as final when the situation requires verification. For official, tax, legal, academic, finance or security decisions, use Toolexa as a helpful working tool and confirm critical details from the right authority or professional.',
            ]],
            ['heading' => 'How the related Toolexa tools help', 'paragraphs' => [
                'The related tools for this article are '.$toolText.'. They are linked below the article so you can move from explanation to action without searching again. Use them as quick helpers for estimates, cleanup, conversion, validation or copying final output.',
                'Each tool page follows the same basic pattern: a focused input area, clear output, supporting content, FAQs and related tools. That consistency matters because once you learn one page, the rest of the Toolexa workflow feels familiar.',
            ]],
            ['heading' => 'A simple checklist before you share the output', 'paragraphs' => [
                'Before sharing a result, ask four quick questions. Did I use the correct input? Did I choose the correct mode? Does the output format match where I will paste or upload it? Would another person understand the result without extra explanation? This short checklist catches many avoidable errors.',
                'For '.$category.' work, the final output often travels into another place: an invoice, spreadsheet, website, report, upload form, code editor, presentation or message. Checking the destination matters because a result that is technically correct can still be unsuitable if the receiving platform expects a different format or level of precision.',
            ]],
            ['heading' => 'How to compare two possible answers', 'paragraphs' => [
                'Many practical tasks involve comparison rather than a single answer. You may compare two loan tenures, two image sizes, two color formats, two conversion methods or two versions of a text result. Put both outputs side by side and compare the difference that actually affects your decision.',
                'When comparing, keep every input the same except the one you want to test. This makes the result easier to understand. If several inputs change at once, you may see a different output but not know which change caused it.',
            ]],
            ['heading' => 'Why this topic matters in daily work', 'paragraphs' => [
                $title.' matters because small decisions often repeat. A single calculation, conversion or generated output may take only a minute, but the same task can appear in invoices, posts, forms, reports, uploads, websites and client messages many times.',
                'Learning the idea behind the tool helps you work faster without becoming careless. You can spot unlikely results, explain your answer and choose the next action with more confidence.',
            ]],
            ['heading' => 'What to document for future reference', 'paragraphs' => [
                'If the result affects a bill, assignment, upload, password, investment estimate or business task, keep a short note of the input values and the date you used them. This makes it easier to explain the result later and repeat the same method when needed.',
                'For finance-related topics, note the rate, tenure, tax assumption or compounding period. For image and developer utilities, note the source format, output format and key settings. These details prevent confusion when you revisit the task after a few days.',
            ]],
            ['heading' => 'How to use the result responsibly', 'paragraphs' => [
                'Online tools are excellent for speed, comparison and everyday productivity, but they should be used with context. A calculator result may depend on rates or rules. A converter result may depend on format support. A text or developer utility may depend on the exact characters copied into the input.',
                'When the result is used for planning, keep a note of assumptions. When it is used for submission, inspect the final output manually. When it affects money, compliance or security, verify the result with an official document, service provider or qualified expert.',
            ]],
            ['heading' => 'How to explain the result to someone else', 'paragraphs' => [
                'A result becomes more useful when you can explain it in one or two sentences. Instead of only sharing the final number or output, mention the input used, the setting selected and the reason the result matters.',
                'For '.$title.', a simple explanation can follow this pattern: "I used these inputs, selected this mode, checked the output against a second example, and this is the conclusion." That small structure makes the answer easier to trust.',
            ]],
            ['heading' => 'When to revisit your calculation or output', 'paragraphs' => [
                'Revisit the result whenever the source information changes. Finance examples may change when rates, tenures, tax rules or contribution amounts change. Image and developer examples may change when the destination platform requires a different size, format, encoding or character limit.',
                'For recurring tasks, save the process rather than only the answer. Bookmark the relevant Toolexa page, keep a note of your common settings and reuse the same workflow next time. Consistency turns a quick online tool into a dependable part of your routine.',
            ]],
        ];
    }
